Look at how intense he is preparing just one dish at a time of the Bak Chor Mee. Lovingly, slowly, each step an elaborate method of preparing a proper bowl. Not for him a rush to serve as many as possible. So this results in a taste unlike most. ....................................................
#SG50Food #SG50Makan #Foodporn:
One creation locally born, infused with mixed origins, is Bak Chor Mee. #traditionalfood #heritagefood 
This version at the Chinatown Smith Street Food Centre #02-023 by "Teochew Street Mushroom Minced Meat Noodle" is one of the best I've tasted. It is painstakingly prepared by this uncle who takes his time in an elaborate ritual to prepare it, one dish at a time. Thus the queue and wait is long but it's one of the few food worth queuing up for. After eating it, unlike other versions that leaves you thirsty, this does not. Check out the other 2 pictures

post_caption:
If you a fan of traditional kopitiam that has not only traditionally brewed authentic coffee aroma but also an old uncle complete in his iconic blue-strip pyjamas, then this time-stood-still coffee shop is for you.  Toasted bread are done over charcoal fire and coffee are done pouring in and out of the brownish-stained coffee bag.  There is even a good olden day timber counter that is no longer used by a cashier, but are stack with traditional biscuits and cookies kept in containers that appear to be used since day one.  If Singapore is serious about preserving its food culture, then this shop has to be gazetted for its intangible cultural heritage that dated back to the 60s and 70s

post_caption:
#SgFoodporn #HawkerFood - Mee Rebus

Via Singapore Infopedia:
Mee rebus is a dish comprising Chinese egg noodles in thick, spicy gravy. Reflecting the multicultural mix of Malaya, the dish contains spices from the Malaya Peninsula and was originally peddled by Indian Muslim migrants.

Description
Rebus in Malay means “to blanch”, so mee rebus refers to “blanched noodles”. Yellow egg noodles are blanched, and then flavoured with a thick gravy. locally as kuah, the gravy is a rich broth of grago (tiny shrimps), flour, sugar and salt. To enhance its flavour, herbs and spices such as lemongrass, ginger and shallots are added to the mix along with meats such as mutton, prawns, ikan bilis (dried anchovies) and even flower crabs.  Traditionally, the gravy is thickened with mashed sweet potato while other variations add ground peanut. A drizzle of dark soya sauce, sliced green chillies and fried shallots top the dish. A slice of limau kesturi (lime) is served on the side to be squeezed over the dish, adding a sour edge. Bean sprouts, a halved hard-boiled egg, thinly sliced tau kwa (fried beancurd) and crispy fried shallots are commonly added as garnish.

Free guided tours of Haw Par Villa and talks, curated and conducted in English and Mandarin by local heritage tour specialist, Journeys. Learn about the history of Haw Par Villa and the brothers (businessmen Aw Boon Haw and Aw Boon Par) behind it, and delve into the Asian philosophy, values and beliefs that inspired the creation of the vivid sculptures and dioramas in the park.

post_caption: Took a walk around one of my favourite areas in Singapore on Sunday after my stay at @hangout_hotels - it's about 20-30mins walk away, doesn't make sense to take the train... Anyway Parkview Square aka the art deco 'Gotham City' building is one of my all time favourite weird architecture.  The story from an ex-client and tenant is that it was positioned due to Fengshui to counter the 'sharp killing' effect of the bladelike Gateway buildings (right) which is bad for wealth! The building's lobby has a lot of gold gilding though some of it is surprisingly ramshackle #latergram #singapore #architecture

post_caption:
I mentioned how impressive the new #IndianHeritageCenter is earlier. Well, one of the must do is to check out the excellent 10 minutes intro film that gives you a excellent summary of the permanent exhibition and what it covers of the history of #Indians in Singapore. The production quality is excellent and I enjoyed it. And hey! I wouldn't mind if my home had a screen like that 😄 One interesting fact I learnt was the crucial role Indian women played  even in the early 20th century and that many of them were educators. That was an interesting fact; that many of them worked and were not just traditional housewives.

post_caption:
I have patronised @thefabulousbakerboy since they started, primarily because of their fabulous cakes and later, their brunch. However, I haven't been back since their renovation which has enlarged their original space and now incoporates an art gallery.

It is nestled at the foot of Fort Canning, in an area called The Foothills that used to be the the River Valley Swimming Pool. I was pleasantly surprised when I step into the place. It was gorgeous - the flowers were blooming, the moon was coming over the trees, the Foothills was a quiet oasis in a clubbing area. It would be perfect for an engagement, wedding or company party. 
I like coming here with friends, to dine in a centrally located chic cafe and chill out with great food.....and did I mention desserts?! The cakes....to die for! Great too for brunch on weekends with families and friends but you must book ahead as it's always fully booked. #Recommended of course!

This Mid-Autumn Festival, @gardensbythebay is offering a brand-new festival experience - with a mixture of both online and offline programmes.

Take a stroll through the gorgeous Apricot Grove or watch the Royal Family's Walk display, which was first displayed at the Seoul Lantern Festival last year.

Another highlight of the festival is the Colonnade of Lights display which showcases 1,500 paper lanterns thoughtfully painted by the community and Gardens by the Bay's senior workers.

Besides these displays, they also offer hands-on activities such as learning how to make a snowskin mooncake or a DIY Good-Luck knot. If you're unable to make it down, you can still participate through the virtual space where exciting performances await you!

The festival and virtual programmes will be launched on 18 Sep and lasts till 4 Oct so mark your calendars now!

Entry is free so share this post with your friends and jio them for a Mid-Autumn outing!

post_caption:
#SgFoodporn - Mee Soto. Yellow noodles with shredded chicken in spicy, tasty broth with begedil. (fried potato patty)

Via Singapore Infopedia: 
Mee soto is a spicy noodle soup dish that combines the Indonesian chicken broth known as soto ayam with thick yellow Hokkien noodles.

Description
The heart of every mee soto dish is the soto ayam(chicken broth). The broth is made from chicken cooked with rempah (spice paste). The ingredients used to prepare the rempah include ginger, garlic, galangal (a type of ginger root), coriander, cumin, fennel, black pepper, nutmeg, curry leaves, belacan (prawn paste) and lemon grass. The trademark yellow hue of the chicken broth comes from the turmeric that is added to therempah. When extra cumin is added, the broth usually turns brownish in colour. When the spicy broth is served with thick yellow Hokkien noodles, it is known as mee soto.

The Quarters was there selling chilli crab man tou, salted egg French fries and their famous Durian Creme Brulee. Despite being full, I decided to give myself a birthday treat and ordered The Durian Creme Bruleee. OMG!! Ecstasy dessert orgasm explosion! My friend sat there amused as I scraped every bit of the too small portion and ate every delicious bit! It really is the best creme brulee out there, better than a lot of restaurants ; and if you love Durians too, I guaranteed you'll fall in love with it like I did the first time I tried it at the pop up at Haw Par Villa by STB. It's decadent without being too sweet or too rich. I normally hate creme brulees but this.....This is like.....best thing ever. I had not eaten it for a while and forgotten how good it was!

⚠️FOMO PROMO ALERT⚠️Chimichanga, Singapore’s first Mexican dive bar, takes us on a journey to rediscover Little India...through a Cocktail Trail! Experience the full process of cocktail making with their in-house cocktail expert, as you hunt for fresh ingredients in Little India’s spice markets and work some cocktail-making magic in this hands-on class.

Running every Sunday from 3pm-6pm, classes are $85 nett per pax and include learning to make 3 Mexican cocktails, a guided sourcing tour, and end off with a set of 3 Tacos of your choice with Nachos and salsa.

Each session is capped at 5 participants, and do remember to observe social distancing and health safety measures for an enjoyable experience 👍🏽

It is believed that the name “Yio Chu Kang” was derived from the early Chinese settlers’ practice of naming a riverside village after the family or clan that settled there or controlled it. Translated, Yio Chu Kang means a Yio (or Yeo) clan/family owns the house (chu) situated along the river (kang).

We had a media preview and walk through of @stevemccurryofficial exhibition at @sundaramtagore Gallery and he took us through some of the stories behind his picture. With this, he talked about how some things are getting lost and becoming ubiquitous, for example these gorgeous red saris the women are wearing. More and more, people are dropping traditional wear and we're all dressing more alike aka Western gear. So his photos are capturing scenes that might not exist down the road. This and the photo behind Steve McCurry are two of my favourites from more than 50 on exhibition. The one behind has amazing details. Check it out when you're there.

Goodbye 74 - 80 Commonwealth Drive: They turned up to say goodbye or to gawk at a slice of old Singapore. Many old residents turned up with their kids, many explaining to their young kids they once lived here. There were also elderly visitors, bent over in half by age, who also turned up. Once, these flats were aspirational and status symbols. Now, just curious relic of a bygone era. 
Watching 7 Letters the movie - love letter to Singapore
............,............,........................... Once 669 families lived in Blocks 74 to 80 at Commonwealth Drive. They were also known as Chap Lau Chu : 10-storey houses in Hokkien. The area is also known as Tanglin Halt, where some of the earliest HDB flats are to be found. The 7 blocks had been identified for redevelopment under Sers and residents moved out to new 40 story flats, nearby. Soon these flats from a bygone era will be demolished.

Today it held its farewell party "Goodbye 74 to 80 Commonwealth Drive" organised by My Queenstown.

It was actually my first time inside the Supreme Court of Singapore attending the launch of the 800th years of the Magna Carta. We frequently hear of it in connection with the American Constitution but its origin is English. It has influenced laws, constitutions of Commonwealth countries. America, Singapore as well as human rights and international laws. So this 800 year old document has historical and present day signifance for its far ranging reach beyond its origins.

The #MagnaCarta @MagnaCarta800th @UKinSingapore One of only four still in existence from 1217, from the Hereford Cathedral in England. On display at the Supreme Court of Singapore for 5 days only.  #Singapore #Sg50

WHEN: Thursday till next Monday, 8.30am to 8pm daily

"Kampong life"
The Last Kampong in Singapore - Appreciate that the last kampong on Singapore’s mainland, not only does Lorong Buangkok serve as an important cultural and historical symbol, I feel that its camaraderie is also something that we can learn from. Residents there welcome each other’s presence and help each other out.
Even though HDB flats attempt to imitate the kampong spirit and induce cohesion among the residents, the camaraderie present is but only a feeble imitation of the kampong spirit.

Kampong Buangkok’s postal code was 1954, when Singapore still used only four digits for postal codes before 1st September 1995. It has since been changed to a six-digit postal code now, but this sign remains as a nostalgic reminder. There's always a sense of warmth and presence of human touch in such a peaceful environment like how friendly Mak Cik (malay auntie) was when I chatted with her. 
Hope this place will be kept and allow the younger generations to learn those valuable lessons we can never learn in class.

Remember to seek Mr and Miss Sng for approval to walk through this wonderful kampong. Seek the residents permission and respect the residents' privacy when are in their premises.

Photography wasn't allowed during the show but we were promised we could shot the cast at the end. Unfortunately the cast came on and got off so fast and as a group and we didn't have enough time or opportunity to really shoot anything! 
Hint: would be better to have individual or more cast calls so we could have instagram it !

From 29 Apr 2015
Fort Canning Park

Shakespeare in the Park - The Tempest : 
Thanks to @alistsg and @singaporerepertorytheatre
We had a fantastic time at the official premier of The Tempest last week. The stage set was absolutely stunning as was the setting in the historic Fort Canning Park under the night sky. Inspired and great setting for The Tempest!
They're on for another 2 weeks.....go!

And a #parrot too. Yep everybody came to the #AndyWarholSocialCircus #TheRyanFoundation #party 

The Ryan Foundation presents: ANDY WARHOL: Social Circus.

Displaying Polaroid photographs of personalities such as Warhol himself, Bianca Jagger, Andre Leon Talley, Tina Chow and Martha Graham, ANDY WARHOL: Social Circus pays homage to Warhol’s iconic studio, The Factory, and avant-garde New York life. Warhol's Polaroids could also be among the first "selfies".

16 – 29 Jan
11am – 7pm
Gillman Barracks
47 Malan Road, #01-26, Singapore 109444

.

“Calliandra haematocephala”

Commonly called red powder puff, is an evergreen shrub or small tree native to Bolivia. 
It was formerly included in the legume or pea family, but has recently been shifted into the mimosa family. 
It typically grows 10-15’ tall in its native habitat and is a very popular flowering shrub in central and southern Florida where it will survive year-round in the ground. 
Uses:
Folkloric • No reported folkloric medicinal use in the Philippines.
• In Nigeria, roots used in the treatment of hemorrhoids. Leaf and root used for measles. • Elsewhere, decoction of the flowers used as blood purifier and tonic.
• In China, flower, leaf, and bark used for its tranquilizing effect.

Each creation has its own uniqueness...

post_caption:
If you ever want to be transported back to a classic Chinese bar in the 1920s, this is your portal hidden away in a quiet corner on Dempsey, beside Min Jiang. With jazzy old Chinese you can sing along to playing at the background, familiar Chinese decor designs, right down to the tableware such as the nuerhong 3-legged cup, you will feel compelled to call the server “小二!” Definitely try their double boiled soup as it comes with a cup of nuerhong, and drink your sorrows away with Baijiu 🍶. Menu provides plenty of explanations for your reading pleasure. Cocktails are pretty unique with Chinese alcohol infusions but comes with a hefty price tag of $26++

#YouCompleteMe ...Still making my friends model #ShareACokeSg while on my current obsession with the #ShareACoke #Sg50 #Singapore campaign. 
From the Coke Singapore website: 
The world-famous ‘Share a Coke’ campaign has arrived on The Little Red Dot and for the first time in Singapore, Coca-Cola cans and bottles will feature nicknames and phrases in place of the iconic Coca-Cola logo, to inspire people to share a Coke with those around them.

In celebration of Singapore’s 50th anniversary, from now until the end of August, Coke™, Coke zero™ and Coke light™ cans and bottles will feature commonly-used Singaporean terms such as “Auntie”, “Uncle”, “Ah Boy” and “Chiongster”; colloquial nicknames such as “BFF”, “Bestie”, “Babe” and “Bro”; classic expressions such as “I Love You” and “You’re the Best” , and favourite Singlish phrases such as “Gam Siah”, “Relak Lah” and “Chiong Ah”. #RediscoveringSingapore #ExploringSingapore #RediscoverSG #ExploreSG #InterestingSingapore #FunInSingapore

HDB Kim Tian 119:

Block 119B, 119C & 119D at Kim Tian Road are 30 storey HDB public housing flats in Bukit Merah, District 03, Singapore. HDB Membina 118:

Membina 118 have Block 118A, 118B, 118C & 118D at Jalan Membina are 30 storey HDB public housing flats in Bukit Merah, District 03, Singapore. It has a total of 172 units with 172 units of 4-room unit type in every block. These flats were completed in 2001 and has a 80 years lease remaining.

#Tradition #Foodporn #Chinese #Dessert #Glutinous #Rice Ball in #Ginger Soup (#Sesame & #Peanut)

I missed the old ah boling stall that used to be sites at the old Chinatown food street. It's disappeared 😢 This one is from Mei Heong Yuen Dessert . There were 4 but I are one up 😄 It's also known as Ah Balling / Tang Yuan and is a traditional Chinese dessert, with glutinous rice balls served in a sweet soup. In Singapore, Ah Balling / Tang Yuan is normally filled with a sweet filling like peanut paste, black sesame paste, red bean paste, and a choice of peanut soup or ginger soup.

Traditionally it is consumed during special occasions like Chinese New Year, or a wedding and holds a special cultural significance for the Chinese, symbolizing family togetherness and unity.

Highlights of the #NationalMuseumofSingapore :
Grease Lighting! Drive in cinemas. Nothing brings back that era than in this recreation under starry starry nights: "Remembering the Jurong drive-in cinema" This  video  installation is inspired  by  the  drive-in cinema in Jurong (1971–1985). One of  Asia’s  largest drive-ins  at  the  time,  the  popular  cinema could  accommodate.
#driveins #driveincinema #driveinmovie ................................................... Had a sneak peek at the National Museum of Singapore's new Permanent galleries. It's been Refreshed, Revamped and Revitalised to better showcase Singapore's history from 700 years ago till present day. It's certainly a fresh look with lots of modern technology incorporated to make the visit more interesting, interactive and immersive. Opens to the public on Sat, Sept 19 with free entry and loads of fun activities for call.
The  new permanent  galleries are  the  Singapore History  Gallery,  the  Life  in  Singapore: The Past  100  Years  galleries  and the  Goh  Seng Choo  Gallery.

Over the past few decades, children’s relationship with the great outdoors and nature has changed dramatically. Most have traded green time for screen time. 

Not only does the loss of children's outdoor play and contact with the natural world negatively impact the growth and development of the whole child and their acquisition of knowledge, it also sets the stage for a continuing loss of the natural environment.

Ok guys......here's something fun for you to do today......how many faces can you spot on this tree trunk?

I took a stroll along Labrador and saw all these nodes in the tree trunk and thought it looked like eyes. After looking at the photo.....I realised there were so faces I could see on the tree trunk!! It's like a totem pole! They look like faces from a totem pole, or a pig's face! There are eyes and noses!! I count about 5 faces including upside down......it's kinda fun but eerie at the same time.

post_caption: Fort Gate, entrance to the British fort completed in 1860. Fort Canning was named after then-Governor-General of India, Lord Charles John Canning. It was built to protect Singapore from seaborne attacks. Fort Gate, the main entrance, faced the beach. A second purpose of the Fort was to be a refuge for the European population in the event of local unrest. #rediscoversg #singaporediscovers #whatmakessg #mysingapore

Everything looks better through the shade of a tree. I wonder if these magnificent #trees will be uprooted and chopped up. How sad. ...............................................................
Once 669 families lived in Blocks 74 to 80 at Commonwealth Drive. They were also known as Chap Lau Chu : 10-storey houses in Hokkien. The area is also known as Tanglin Halt, where some of the earliest HDB flats are to be found. The 7 blocks had been identified for redevelopment under Sers and residents moved out to new 40 story flats, nearby. Soon these flats from a bygone era will be demolished.

Today it held its farewell party "Goodbye 74 to 80 Commonwealth Drive" organised by My Queenstown.

The Ryan Foundation presents: ANDY WARHOL: Social Circus.

Displaying Polaroid photographs of personalities such as Warhol himself, Bianca Jagger, Andre Leon Talley, Tina Chow and Martha Graham, ANDY WARHOL: Social Circus pays homage to Warhol’s iconic studio, The Factory, and avant-garde New York life. Warhol's Polaroids could also be among the first "selfies".

post_caption:
Making all my friends model #ShareACokeSg while on my current obsession with the #ShareACoke #Sg50 #Singapore campaign. Yesterday got #BFF as in thank you every one I met this week for lunch dinner tea fireworks tours and more! 
From the Coke Singapore website: 
The world-famous ‘Share a Coke’ campaign has arrived on The Little Red Dot and for the first time in Singapore, Coca-Cola cans and bottles will feature nicknames and phrases in place of the iconic Coca-Cola logo, to inspire people to share a Coke with those around them.

In celebration of Singapore’s 50th anniversary, from now until the end of August, Coke™, Coke zero™ and Coke light™ cans and bottles will feature commonly-used Singaporean terms such as “Auntie”, “Uncle”, “Ah Boy” and “Chiongster”; colloquial nicknames such as “BFF”, “Bestie”, “Babe” and “Bro”; classic expressions such as “I Love You” and “You’re the Best” , and favourite Singlish phrases such as “Gam Siah”, “Relak Lah” and “Chiong Ah”. #RediscoveringSingapore #ExploringSingapore #RediscoverSG #ExploreSG #InterestingSingapore #FunInSingapore

post_caption:
Last night for the @thecomedyclubsg #SgComedyFringe . I had a great time in Wed watching established and new #Singapore #comedic talents take to the stage, providing much needed laughter mid-week. My earlier review:

#WednesdayNightLaughter at the thecomedyclubsg SgComedyFringe #comedy show "SONS OF SINGAPORE" tonight - featuring the incomparably #Kumar who kept us hysterically laughing throughout with localised #jokes that were maybe politically incorrect but never offensive or insensitive. It's the special Kumar charm. He was clearly the crowd favourite.

Also appearing were Fakkah Fuzz, Rishi Budhrani and Jinx Yeo - 3 rising comedy stars ; a Malay, an Indian and a Chinese, representing the multi-racial make up of Singapore and jokes about Singaporeans. Fuzz was clearly the most experienced of the 3, Rishi was polished and Jinx seemingly the newbie of the group. They ranged from pretty good to oh oh.....that fell flat and was kinda insensitive but overall the audience was an appreciative lot and were kept laughing and cheering throughout.

Pity the "SONS OF SINGAPORE"  is one night only - the full house certainly testified to the enduring popularity and draw of Kumar and company. 
The Singapore 2015 Comedy Fringe plays till Saturday 13th June with 6 more sets of #comedians from different countries. Catch one - #laughter is really the best medicine ! http://www.thecomedyclub.asia/home/

My favourite moment of the night at the THE FUNDAMENTALLY FABULOUS PARTY at @thefabulousbakerboy - When the Chef Juwanda Hassim thanked his good friend, theatre, stage and TV star Pam Oei for believing in him all those years ago and inspiring the name of the chic cafe.

We all need friends who believe in our dreams and keep believing in it many many years down the road.

In honour of Pam, he named his latest creation , the "Pam D'Or" - a decadent #gateau of brown butter sponge filled with Medjool dates and spices, with 4 layers of butterscotch and cream cheese , covered with Swiss meringue butter cream with a coat of Valrhona chocolate. A cake befitting the multi- talented Pam Oei who sang a wonderful tribute in this gorgeous rich voice that was surprising coming from such a dimunitive talent.

post_caption:
#Foodporn : I was out at the #neighbourhood #Indian store when I came across this #coconut #candy #sweet from my #childhood days. So I bought a pack but forgot whether it had another name apart from coconut candy and it's origins. So I asked FB 😄 Back came a recipe and helpful answer. It's made from dessicated coconut, condensed milk, sugar, milk, food colouring and food essense like rose or vanilla. Kind of a #fudge I guess!

As to it's probably origins, here's the reply:
"Basically, this sweet known popularly as coconut candy in Sg has its origins in the land of sweets - India. 
This is a traditional South Indian sweet known as Tenga Barfi (Tenga meaning coconut and Barfi meaning a hardened square shape sweet). This has variations across India and in North India this is called Khopra Paak(Khopra meaning the coconut).
This coconut candy is a hybrid version of this sweet - typically the Singaporeanised Asian version. "

post_caption:
Old & New
Toa Payoh Lorong 6 Dragon Playground
(Singapore Heritage)

The dragon-shaped sand-based playground used to be a popular design for playgrounds in Ang Mo Kio and Toa Payoh.

After 1993, they were phased out due to safety concerns and it is believed that this Dragon Playground of Toa Payoh (located at Blk 28 Toa Payoh Lorong 6) is the only one of its kinds (sand-based) left in Singapore (The other two are laid with rubber mats).

The dragon playground was designed in 1979 by Housing and  Development Board’s (HDB) in-house designer Khor Ean Ghee (born 1935), who got his inspiration from the Oriental dragon commonly seen among the Chinese community in Singapore.

Beside the majestic dragon, there are two little plastic rides in the shapes of a seahorse and a pony for children to sit on.

The long body of the dragon is made of steel rails which form a passage for kids to get to the dragon head. Using the slide, kids can descend from the dragon head to the sandy ground.

The Toa Payoh dragon playground was picked by New York culture blog, Flavorwire.com, in 2013 as one of 15 amazing playgrounds from all over the world.

HDB Toa Payoh Apex (Background):

HDB Toa Payoh Apex is bounded by Lorong 6 Toa Payoh and Toa Payoh East, approximately 10 minutes (1.1km) walk away from Toa Payoh MRT Station. 

This development consist of 557 units of 3- and 4-room Standard Flats. All 4 blocks of flats come with three-quarter height windows in the living/ dining area and half-height windows in other rooms. Highest floor is 36 storey.

post_caption:
A kampong's beauty
.
The Last Kampong in Singapore - Appreciate that the last kampong on Singapore’s mainland, not only does Lorong Buangkok serve as an important cultural and historical symbol, I feel that its camaraderie is also something that we can learn from. Residents there welcome each other’s presence and help each other out.
Even though HDB flats attempt to imitate the kampong spirit and induce cohesion among the residents, the camaraderie present is but only a feeble imitation of the kampong spirit.

Kampong Buangkok’s postal code was 1954, when Singapore still used only four digits for postal codes before 1st September 1995. It has since been changed to a six-digit postal code now, but this sign remains as a nostalgic reminder. There's always a sense of warmth and presence of human touch in such a peaceful environment like how friendly Mak Cik (malay auntie) was when I chatted with her. 
Hope this place will be kept and allow the younger generations to learn those valuable lessons we can never learn in class.

Remember to seek Mr and Miss Sng for approval to walk through this wonderful kampong. Seek the residents permission and respect the residents' privacy when are in their premises.

Jurong Lake Garden Playground 
Forest Ramble
Situated at the West side of Singapore, the dry playground is huge, with 13 play areas. Most of the play structures were designed to blend with their natural surroundings.
There are swings, a few climbing structures (some which were still closed during phase 2 reopening), trampolines and jumping areas, wood balance play structures, sand play, and water play using pumps. 
The sand areas feature logs that children can use as balancing beams.
There are quite a few animals roaming around that we got to see up close. Slide to see how the boys saw the water lizard passing by.
Definitely one of the playgrounds one can bring the children over and over.

post_caption: Discovered this lovely @shukuuizakaya serving sumi-yaki (charcoal grilled food) and agemono,  with a modern twist. Mario,  the chef-partner was a designer by profession; he personally decorated the place -  cosy with plenty of character,  down to the manga-ish menu. The  #kushiyaki assorted skewers with meat and vegetables were perfectly grilled, and the Tori Kara-Age of chunky deep-fried garlic soya #chicken was succulent. The yaki onigiri was one of the best I'd tried, moist rice lightly flavored and grilled. Unusual items were the rosti with mentiako, and the Parmesan chips with tomato and honey.  #sgmemory #yoursingapore #interestingsingapore #igsg #artists #rediscoversg  #sgig  #rediscoveringsingapore #sgheritage #sg50 #arts #jj_editors #igsingapore #exploringsingapore #sgnightfestival #singaporeinsiders #sgfood #foodporn #style #yummy #izakaya #japanesefood #grilled

You can't miss this golden sheet at the @nationalgallerysingapore that seems to shade but in fact connects both the  former City Hall and Supreme Court. It also throws interesting designs inside on sunny days. 
From Straits Times :
Starting at the Supreme Court wing, extending over the former alleyway between the buildings and running along the length of City Hall, the flat glass, steel and aluminium structure links the two monuments as one institution. More than 15,000 aluminium panels of varying patterns and perforations in varied shades of gold allow for a stunning play of light on a bright day. Supporting the roof and the veil of panels are five tree-like steel structures which are between 12m and 30m tall.  #ArchitectureHeritageAwards #ahasg2015 #design  #Singapore #CityHall #SupremeCourt  #NationalGallerySg  #NationalGallerySingapore  #SouthEastAsia #art

The word chapat (चपत) in Hindi means "to slap", and the traditional method of forming rounds of thin dough is by slapping the dough between the wetted palms of the hands. With each slap, the round of dough is rotated.

post_caption: 戏终人散 The desolate cinema waiting for it's imminent fate.

It’s that time of the week again for the East Coast Food Plan! This week, we’ll be exploring Simei! It might be small, but when it comes to food wars, they are definitely a force to be reckoned with.

Hola Cafeteria
Hola Cafeteria is the go-to food court in Simei! Check out San Bao Ban Mian’s Dry Banmian ($4) and the Cantonese Porridge stall’s Sliced Fish Porridge ($4). Jiaxiang Pancakes also offers savoury Min Jiang Kuehs such as the Cheese + Egg Pancake ($1.70).

📍 248 Simei Street 3, S(520248)

LOR Duck
We have great news for fans of the famous Redhill Lor Duck Rice and Noodles that closed in early 2017. They’re back with @lorducklefeng! Their Signature Braised Duck ($8-$48) is succulent and tender. They also offer Braised Pork Belly and Tofu ($14-$48) if you aren’t a duck lover!

📍 3 Simei Street 6, #01-33 Eastpoint, S(528833)

Malaysia Boleh
Missing those weekend getaways to JB? Indulge in heartwarming dishes at @malaysiabolehsg  which resembles Malaysian food streets! Popular dishes include the Char Kway Teow ($4.5-$6) and Cendol ($2).

📍 #04-04, 3 Simei Street 6, Eastpoint Mall, S(528833)

Metta Cafe
Set up by Metta Welfare Association, @mettacafe1 serves affordable yet delicious food such as Tom Yam Fried Bee Hoon ($4.50) and Latte at only $1! At the same time, they also provide vocational F&B training for Metta School graduates with mild intellectual disability and/or autism.

📍 Metta Building Level 1, 32 Simei Street 1, S(529950)

Mirana Cake House
This quaint bakery will transport you back to your childhood with their scrumptious old-school bakes such as Mini Butter Cream Cakes ($22 for 20pcs) and Char Siew Buns ($1.30). They also offer next-day delivery so you’ll never have to worry about buying last-minute birthday cakes!

📍 248 Simei Street 3, #01-102, Singapore 520248

If you’re a fan of the East Coast Food Plan, give us a like and share it to your IG stories! Comment below other places you want us to feature 👇🏻.

It's been Refreshed, Revamped and Revitalised to better showcase Singapore's history from 700 years ago till present day. It's certainly a fresh look with lots of modern technology incorporated to make the visit more interesting, interactive and immersive. Opens to the public on Sat, Sept 19 with free entry and loads of fun activities for all.

The  new permanent galleries are  the Singapore History  Gallery,  the  Life in Singapore: The Past 100  Years galleries and the Goh Seng Choo Gallery.

Weekend supper at Wanton Noodle Bar, down by Amoy Street. It reminded me of hip noodle bars like Momofuku in USA. The noodle recipe is apparently from the famous Seng’s Wanton Mee of Dunman Food Centre. I suggest trying dinner or supper as, quoting its website, “The night menu sees a deconstruction of the noodles – ingredients are enhanced and imbued with a modern twist. Pick from a range of addictive sides such as Roasted Spanish Pork Belly, Batalong Egg (local version of the Scotch Egg) and even seasonal fresh greens.” You help yourself to free-flow of hearty broth in thermos; and I like that you can add your own condiments like black soy sauce, #pork lard pieces, sesame oil and pickled green chilli; and of course the famous chilli sauce, which was rather good. The #egg noodles were springy and the lard that it was tossed in was surprisingly very palatable. At S$2.50 a bowl, you can’t complain considering the locale. The fun part is ordering the sides - don't miss the roasted pork belly; it's very delish! The bar features a decent selection of signature cocktails, craft beers and even #sake.  #sgmemory #yoursingapore #interestingsingapore #igsg #rediscoversg  #sgig #rediscoveringsingapore #sgheritage #sg50 #jj_editors #igsingapore #exploringsingapore #glitzglamour #sgnightfestival #singaporeinsiders #sgfood

Once 669 families lived in Blocks 74 to 80 at Commonwealth Drive. They were also known as Chap Lau Chu : 10-storey houses in Hokkien. The area is also known as Tanglin Halt, where some of the earliest HDB flats are to be found. The 7 blocks had been identified for redevelopment under Sers and residents moved out to new 40 story flats, nearby. Soon these flats from a bygone era will be demolished.

Today it held its farewell party "Goodbye 74 to 80 Commonwealth Drive" organised by My Queenstown.

What I loved at the revamped #NationalMuseumofSingapore: this beautiful #silk pair of #vintage ladies #shoes. So delicately beautiful "The pink  satin  high-heeled shoes  with floral  embroidery,  for  example,  are  decorated  with  both  a  huge  bow  and  an  embroidered  peony  motif in the centre.  The crossed  straps  over  the instep  fastened  with  buttons  make them  appropriate for ballroom dancing, which had become very popular in Singapore by the 1920s. " ................................................... Had a sneak peek at the National Museum of Singapore's new Permanent galleries. It's been Refreshed, Revamped and Revitalised to better showcase Singapore's history from 700 years ago till present day. It's certainly a fresh look with lots of modern technology incorporated to make the visit more interesting, interactive and immersive. Opens to the public on Sat, Sept 19 with free entry and loads of fun activities for call.
The  new permanent  galleries are  the  Singapore History  Gallery,  the  Life  in  Singapore: The Past  100  Years  galleries  and the  Goh  Seng Choo  Gallery.

Every one is a star ....well for a minute tonight anyway! 

The most popular happening at the happening #AndyWarholSocialCircus party by #TheRyanFoundation was the #polaroid corner. Before there were selfish and Instagram, #AndyWarhol had his ever present Polaroid camera with which he took ultra glamorous shots of the most famous and beautiful celebrities of the day. 

The Ryan Foundation presents: ANDY WARHOL: Social Circus.

Displaying Polaroid photographs of personalities such as Warhol himself, Bianca Jagger, Andre Leon Talley, Tina Chow and Martha Graham, ANDY WARHOL: Social Circus pays homage to Warhol’s iconic studio, The Factory, and avant-garde New York life. Warhol's Polaroids could also be among the first "selfies".

ANDY WARHOL: SOCIAL CIRCUS
16 – 29 Jan
11am – 7pm
Gillman Barracks
47 Malan Road, #01-26, Singapore 109444
Free admission

The most popular happening at the happening #AndyWarholSocialCircus party by #TheRyanFoundation was the #polaroid corner. Before there were selfish and Instagram, #AndyWarhol had his ever present Polaroid camera with which he took ultra glamorous shots of the most famous and beautiful celebrities of the day. 

Here @mariaelenarudolf of Art Stage Singapore poses with her friends.

The Ryan Foundation presents: ANDY WARHOL: Social Circus.

Displaying Polaroid photographs of personalities such as Warhol himself, Bianca Jagger, Andre Leon Talley, Tina Chow and Martha Graham, ANDY WARHOL: Social Circus pays homage to Warhol’s iconic studio, The Factory, and avant-garde New York life. Warhol's Polaroids could also be among the first "selfies".

ANDY WARHOL: SOCIAL CIRCUS
16 – 29 Jan
11am – 7pm

The view from the three story #SingaporeYuHuangGong temple is pretty special and interesting. It gives you an idea of what the area would have looked like a century ago, with the sea at its front doors. It includes a view to the neighbouring temple, the equally historic Thian Hock Keng temple. ................................................... . .....................This little gem of a #Taoist #temple on Telok Ayer Street was kept hidden for over a hundred years. This is the national #monument, the Singapore 'Yu Huang Gong', Temple of The Heavenly Jade Emperor, located at 150 Telok Ayer Streer. Extensive restoration work was undertaken last few years to save the historic 170-year-old temple and has now been completed.

I saw this pretty #Rangoli earlier when I was at the library.

Wiki: Rangoli, also known as Kolam or Muggu, is a folk art from India in which patterns are created on the floor in living rooms or courtyards using materials such as colored rice, dry flour, colored sand or flower petals. It is usually made during Diwali (Deepawali), Onam, Pongal and other Indian festivals. They are meant to be sacred welcoming areas for the Hindu deities .

post_caption:
So loving the #SG50 @CocaColaSG #ShareACoke #Singapore campaign. #Best ever. Got #Chio as in #Chiobu as in pretty or cute girl, a #Hokkien term so ...hey! Thank you!

From the Coke Singapore website: 
The world-famous ‘Share a Coke’ campaign has arrived on The Little Red Dot and for the first time in Singapore, Coca-Cola cans and bottles will feature nicknames and phrases in place of the iconic Coca-Cola logo, to inspire people to share a Coke with those around them.

In celebration of Singapore’s 50th anniversary, from now until the end of August, Coke™, Coke zero™ and Coke light™ cans and bottles will feature commonly-used Singaporean terms such as “Auntie”, “Uncle”, “Ah Boy” and “Chiongster”; colloquial nicknames such as “BFF”, “Bestie”, “Babe” and “Bro”; classic expressions such as “I Love You” and “You’re the Best” , and favourite Singlish phrases such as “Gam Siah”, “Relak Lah” and “Chiong Ah”. #RediscoveringSingapore #ExploringSingapore #RediscoverSG #ExploreSG #InterestingSingapore #FunInSingapore

I enjoyed the #TelokAyerStreetLightUp , part of the #SingaporeHeritageFest , especially the #traditional #fuzhou #DragonDance by @sg_xinyang_yongyang 
From Wiki:
Dragon dance (simplified Chinese: 舞龙;traditional Chinese: 舞龍; pinyin: wǔ lóng) is a form of traditional dance and performance inChinese culture. Like the lion dance it is most often seen in festive celebrations. The dance is performed by a team of dancers who manipulate a long flexible figure of a dragon using poles positioned at regular intervals along the length of the dragon. The dance team mimics the supposed movements of this river spirit in a sinuous, undulating manner.

The dragon dance is often performed duringChinese New Year. Chinese dragons are a symbol of China, and they are believed to bring good luck to people, therefore the longer the dragon in the dance, the more luck it will bring to the community.[1] The dragons are believed to possess qualities that include great power, dignity, fertility, wisdom and auspiciousness.

Had a friend back in town from Toulouse so took her down to one of the Singapore Food Festival 2015 events - A Wok Down Memory Lane at Ellenborough Market - meant to recreate the time when it was the largest food and traders markets from late 1800 to late 60s when it burnt down in 1968.

We had a great meal there though. Thanks to a recommendation , I had the Pig's Trotters Lor Mee. Highly recommended. We also had Good Chance Popiah. I've been to their restaurant at Silat Road before. 
My friend also ordered Kuay Pie Tee and Laksa.

A Wok Down Memory Lane at Ellenborough Market
24 Jul - 2 Aug, 5PM – 11PM daily

Jubilee Walk Tour Point 9: Singapore River. Clarke Quay

Clarke Quay is located along the Singapore River and from the early 1800s, served as a dock for the loading and unloading of cargoes for the godowns (warehouses) and commercial houses situated along the Singapore River. 
Clarke Quay is named after Sir Andrew Clarke, Governor of the Straits Settlements from 1824 to 1902. Now it has been redeveloped and the restored warehouses houses restaurants, bars and clubs.

Prinsep Street Presbyterian Church was founded as the Malay Chapel in 1843 by Reverend Benjamin Keasberry of the London Missionary Society. It became known as the Straits Chinese Presbyterian Church under the English Presbyterian Mission in 1886 and acquired its present name in 1955. The present sanctuary was built in 1950, and was gazetted as a National Monument in 2000. #rediscoversg #whatmakessg #mysingapore #nationalmonument #heritage

post_caption:
Koon Seng Road electric shophouses have been gazetted for conservation due to its 𝗵𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗼𝗿𝘆 & 𝗵𝗲𝗿𝗶𝘁𝗮𝗴𝗲 𝘃𝗮𝗹𝘂𝗲. With a hybridised blend of cultural injections, these shophouses still managed to showcase a uniformity in its 𝗮𝗿𝗰𝗵𝗶𝘁𝗲𝗰𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲 & 𝗱𝗲𝘀𝗶𝗴𝗻, making it an #instaworthy spot for many locals & tourists.⁠
⁠
The external walls of these shophouses are decorated with Chinese couplets of good fortune, adorning entrances which are similar to the traditional residences in China. Shophouses were designed with 𝗳𝗹𝗼𝗿𝗮𝗹 & 𝗴𝗲𝗼𝗺𝗲𝘁𝗿𝗶𝗰𝗮𝗹 𝗰𝗲𝗿𝗮𝗺𝗶𝗰 𝘁𝗶𝗹𝗲𝘀 that were imported from Europe.⁠
⁠
⁠Furthermore, the various 𝗺𝗼𝘁𝗶𝗳𝘀 𝗼𝗻 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗳𝗮𝗰𝗮𝗱𝗲𝘀 are derived from mythical figures, which are usually symbols of good fortune & longevity, and reflected the wealth & status of the owner.⁠
⁠
Many elements of the 𝗞𝗼𝗼𝗻 𝗦𝗲𝗻𝗴 𝗣𝗿𝗲-𝗪𝗮𝗿 𝗦𝗵𝗼𝗽𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘀𝗲𝘀 are reflected in the designs of our hotel. ⁠
What other designs in our hotel have surprised you?⁠
_________________________⁠
#RediscoverSingapore @hotelindigo #anIHGhotel #Katong⁠

The cast and creator of the new interactive #play "The Greatest Treasure in the World" at the @natmuseum_sg taking a now at the end of the first #performance. 

Created and conceptualize by Peggy Ferroa, a Community Artist,  it ties in with the current #exhibition "Treasures of the World from the British Museum " incorporating highlights and elements from the exhibition as well as incorporating  #audience participation and interaction. We enjoyed the play and I thought it a great idea to incorporate and integrate the exhibit and the play.

Exhibition Galleries 1 & 2, Basement
28 Jan 2016 - 30 Apr 2016
7.30pm & 9pm (approx. 60 mins without intermission) $38 "What happens when you stray into the National Museum’s Treasures of the World exhibition after dark? Well, you’ll meet Afonso, the curious Portuguese sailor who journeyed with Vasco da Gama in 1503. "

These unique Singapore Local Flavours Egg Tarts cannot be bought anywhere other than ⁣at @honeyhomebakes! They will be launching them as part of their bake sale next Thursday, 22nd October. If you are a fan of savoury local dishes like chilli crab, nasi lemak, satay, curry potato and hae bee hiam, you are sure to love this set of egg tarts! I loved how generous the fillings were - you could really taste each flavour very distinctly. The pastry was also perfectly flaky, and the egg custard filling was a nice balance of sweet and salty. Kudos to @honeyhomebakes for the incredible amount of effort that no doubt must have gone into the R&D of these egg tarts! @honeyhomebakes also sells madeleines in a variety of interesting flavours, do check out their profile to find out more.

Built in the 1850s, Yueh Hai Ching is Singapore’s oldest Teochew temple. It started as a makeshift shrine in the 1820s dedicated to Mazu, Goddess of the Sea. It was gazetted as a National Monument in 1996. #rediscoversg #mysingapore

Onde onde at Spice Zi kitchen - beautiful green balls flecked with bits of orange? What's that? 

Sweet potato 😊

Mama zi says sweet potato makes the dough sweeter and also softer and less gummy. 

Also, when we make onde onde, we cut out square chunks of gula melaka and pop it into each ball. These sugar chunks don't melt out entirely until you put them in your mouth😏😏

post_caption:
A timely reminder to all in this COVID-19 Pandemic; Singapore's Ok! sculpture Park was built after Singapore successfully won the SARS outbreak in 2003. 

Each finger represent a message:
1) Eat healthy, exercise regularly 
2) Wash hand with soap frequently
3) Do not litter. Bag your rubbish and place in bin
4) See doctor, avoid crowded places if unwell. Spit, cough and sneeze into tissue
5) Keep public toilet clean. Keep places clean and free of pests.

post_caption:
#Japanese #Foodporn in #Singapore:
I hadn't even realised the Aijensen shop in a corner of Parkway had been taken over by fame celebrity #Chef Keisuke Takeda's chain - Ramen Keisuke Tonkotsu King MATSURI.

The food and the decor is based around the #Japanese MATSURI theme - this is a sorta of cultural festival celebration. There's a crazy fierce oversized  #Nebuta  ornament  from  Aomori, which usually  depicts  historical  and cultural  figures and  in  large-scale  brilliantly  painted  paper  #lanterns. 
There's also a series of paintings that a waiter assured us cost a bomb at $20,000 per painting! Kinda surreal

post_caption:
Tonight my friend and I ordered #Coke and we got #ShareACoke #Wifey and #Hon together! #LOL 
This is the localised #Singapore #Sg50 edition of the most successful Coca-Cola worldwide campaign in decades.

From the Coke Singapore website: 
The world-famous ‘Share a Coke’ campaign has arrived on The Little Red Dot and for the first time in Singapore, Coca-Cola cans and bottles will feature nicknames and phrases in place of the iconic Coca-Cola logo, to inspire people to share a Coke with those around them.

In celebration of Singapore’s 50th anniversary, from now until the end of August, Coke™, Coke zero™ and Coke light™ cans and bottles will feature commonly-used Singaporean terms such as “Auntie”, “Uncle”, “Ah Boy” and “Chiongster”; colloquial nicknames such as “BFF”, “Bestie”, “Babe” and “Bro”; classic expressions such as “I Love You” and “You’re the Best” , and favourite Singlish phrases such as “Gam Siah”, “Relak Lah” and “Chiong Ah”. #RediscoveringSingapore #ExploringSingapore #RediscoverSG #ExploreSG #InterestingSingapore #FunInSingapore

#Foodporn #Singapore #Indian - last few festive days of #Deepavali pre-festivities in #LittleIndia . Took a walk around, saw the lights, shop at the bazaars, had Teh Halia at a corner hole in the world and saw the preparation of this through a window so went in and tried Sev Puri Chaat, which turned out to be a #snack ! 
From Wiki:
Sev puri is an Indian snack and a type ofchaat. It is a speciality that originates fromMumbai. In Mumbai, sev puri is served by street vendors as well as five star hotels.Recently, supermarkets have started stocking ready-to-eat packets of sev puri and similar snacks like bhelpuri.

Although there is no fixed recipe for sev puri, the basic ingredients used widely are the same. Sev puri is essentially made of puriwhich is loaded with diced potatoes, onions, three types of chutneys:  tamarind, chili andgarlic and topped with sev. It is seasoned with raw mango, when raw mango is in season or with a hint of lemon and chaat masala.

Knock knock - who's there? Found this nostalgic little nook by chance! #latergram

Old & New
Toa Payoh Lorong 6 Dragon Playground
(Singapore Heritage)

The dragon-shaped sand-based playground used to be a popular design for playgrounds in Ang Mo Kio and Toa Payoh.

After 1993, they were phased out due to safety concerns and it is believed that this Dragon Playground of Toa Payoh (located at Blk 28 Toa Payoh Lorong 6) is the only one of its kinds (sand-based) left in Singapore (The other two are laid with rubber mats).

The dragon playground was designed in 1979 by Housing and  Development Board’s (HDB) in-house designer Khor Ean Ghee (born 1935), who got his inspiration from the Oriental dragon commonly seen among the Chinese community in Singapore.

Beside the majestic dragon, there are two little plastic rides in the shapes of a seahorse and a pony for children to sit on.

The long body of the dragon is made of steel rails which form a passage for kids to get to the dragon head. Using the slide, kids can descend from the dragon head to the sandy ground.

The Toa Payoh dragon playground was picked by New York culture blog, Flavorwire.com, in 2013 as one of 15 amazing playgrounds from all over the world.

HDB Toa Payoh Apex (Background):

HDB Toa Payoh Apex is bounded by Lorong 6 Toa Payoh and Toa Payoh East, approximately 10 minutes (1.1km) walk away from Toa Payoh MRT Station. 

This development consist of 557 units of 3- and 4-room Standard Flats. All 4 blocks of flats come with three-quarter height windows in the living/ dining area and half-height windows in other rooms. Highest floor is 36 storey.
The Haw Par Villa gate - for the non-Chinese, Hu/Haw is tiger, Pao/Par is leopard, which were also the names of the Chinese brothers who set up this bizarre park. #hawparvilla

With roots dating back to 17th century northern Kerala, Krishnattam is an all-male temple dance drama that tells the story of Lord Krishna over a series of eight plays. Created by Manaveda, the Zamorin raja (king) of Calicut, in 1653, the play is performed today only at the temple dedicated to Lord Krishna in the town of Guruvayoor. With its intricate costumes, makeup, as well as highly stylised combination of dance and theatre, it is believed that a Krishnattam performance bestows blessings upon its audience.

post_caption:
Who likes mushy food? 

@kaamelology is one of those in the family who likes all things mushy and soft. 

Mama zi makes this cauliflower dish for her youngest daughter by cooking the cauli and lentils in the pressure cooker, then sautes the soft vegetables with onions, chili, curry leaves, turmeric, chilli powder, mustard seeds and lastly throws in ground coconut. 

This dish is usually eaten with chapatti or rice but this time round, our guests had it with mee siam briyani 😊

#ShareACokeSg while on my current obsession with the #ShareACoke #Sg50 #Singapore campaign. 
From the Coke Singapore website: 
The world-famous ‘Share a Coke’ campaign has arrived on The Little Red Dot and for the first time in Singapore, Coca-Cola cans and bottles will feature nicknames and phrases in place of the iconic Coca-Cola logo, to inspire people to share a Coke with those around them.

In celebration of Singapore’s 50th anniversary, from now until the end of August, Coke™, Coke zero™ and Coke light™ cans and bottles will feature commonly-used Singaporean terms such as “Auntie”, “Uncle”, “Ah Boy” and “Chiongster”; colloquial nicknames such as “BFF”, “Bestie”, “Babe” and “Bro”; classic expressions such as “I Love You” and “You’re the Best” , and favourite Singlish phrases such as “Gam Siah”, “Relak Lah” and “Chiong Ah”. #RediscoveringSingapore #ExploringSingapore #RediscoverSG #ExploreSG #InterestingSingapore #FunInSingapore

post_caption:
I was pleasantly surprised to come across these #sg50moovecows from #moovemediaoutdoor and thought they were delightfully cute! Love them all.....here's the Satay Man, the Nonya, Trishaw Man and Ma Jie. "One of my favourite #SG50MooveCows is Nyonya lady because it reminds me of my Peranakan nanny and granny. My hope for the future is a peaceful co-existing, multi-ethnic Singapore." Info extracted Via Marketing:
Moove Media’s iconic cows can be seen all over the island in celebration of SG50.
The SG50 Moove cow, which stands at 1.76m each, will represent eight historical characters – the Coolie, the Rickshaw Man, the Kacang Puteh Man, the Satay Man, the domestic helper or “Ma Jie”, the Samsui Woman, the Nyonya as well as the Wayang Opera Diva.
The cows will also go on sale from 13 July onwards and proceeds from the sale will go towards the Home Improvement Fund that ComfortDelGro has set up to help improve the quality of living of the elderly of the Lions Befrienders Service Association (Singapore). #RediscoveringSingapore #ExploringSingapore #RediscoverSG #ExploreSG #InterestingSingapore #FunInSingapore

"Chamber of God" by Mujahidin Nurrahman @artstagesg D4

I stumbled across this beautiful and thought provoking piece by talented Bandung artist Mujahidin Nurrahman as I was leaving #ArtStageSg. I spent the most time checking out the gorgeous installation piece and was lucky to hear the story behind the inspiration for Chambers of God. The installation art piece was borne out of the Artist's desire to discuss the issue of war and conflict in the Middle East, how the world sees Islam and Muslims and includes a tie back to World War UK in the form of old photos and gas mask found in the flea markets of Paris. He painstakingly cut out the intricate Arabesque patterns on the screen and canvases. Go check it out if you're there. I thought it would be great for the Singapore Biennial actually. 

ART STAGE SINGAPORE
21 - 24 Jan, 12:00 PM - 6:00 PM
Marina Bay Singapore
@marinabaysg

《Exploring Singapore》

Art doesn’t have to be found on the walls of a gallery. While Singapore certainly has its share of world-class museums, exhibitions and art spaces, it’s also home to a wealth of street art and iconic wall murals.

Go on a hunt through Singapore’s diverse neighbourhoods—from the South Asian enclave of Little India to the lively streets of Chinatown—and discover art that will both inspire and expand your artistic sensibilities.

Grandlink Square, with the front facade of the former queen's theatre.

It used to be an entertainment place until it ceased its operation in 1982. Today, the current building is occupied by Grandlink square, retaining the front facade.  The facade now is under the conservation area of URA (Urban Redevelopment Authority).

Rediscovering Sg means to walk around the neighbourhood instead of taking public transport because who knows we might spot a hidden gem at the corner of the street, which led me to this historical place.

Highlights from the new permanent galleries of the #NationalMuseumofSingapore : 
Women’s  shoes Late 19th  century  to  1920s Beads,  cotton,  sequins,  leather,  gold  thread,  plastic,  velvet,  suede,  silk  satin  and  wood Shanghai,  China,  Singapore. Including this tiny  pair  of  embroidered silk  shoes  for  bound feet that was  typical  of  those worn  by  women  in  wealthy  Chinese  families,  symbolising  beauty  and  status  in  Singapore  during  the late and early  20th century.  Measuring just  3 inches  long,  the  wearer’s  feet  would  have  been crushed and  wrapped  in  bandages  since  she  was  young.  #vintage #shoes #fashion
................................................... ...........................Had a sneak peek at the National Museum of Singapore's new Permanent galleries. It's been Refreshed, Revamped and Revitalised to better showcase Singapore's history from 700 years ago till present day. It's certainly a fresh look with lots of modern technology incorporated to make the visit more interesting, interactive and immersive. Opens to the public on Sat, Sept 19 with free entry and loads of fun activities for all.

The  new permanent galleries are  the Singapore History  Gallery,  the  Life in Singapore: The Past 100 Years galleries and the Goh Seng Choo Gallery.

#PhotoGrid  #Coke  #ShareACoke
This is the localised #Singapore #Sg50 edition of the most successful Coca-Cola worldwide campaign in decades.

From the Coke Singapore website: 
The world-famous ‘Share a Coke’ campaign has arrived on The Little Red Dot and for the first time in Singapore, Coca-Cola cans and bottles will feature nicknames and phrases in place of the iconic Coca-Cola logo, to inspire people to share a Coke with those around them.

In celebration of Singapore’s 50th anniversary, from now until the end of August, Coke™, Coke zero™ and Coke light™ cans and bottles will feature commonly-used Singaporean terms such as “Auntie”, “Uncle”, “Ah Boy” and “Chiongster”; colloquial nicknames such as “BFF”, “Bestie”, “Babe” and “Bro”; classic expressions such as “I Love You” and “You’re the Best” , and favourite Singlish phrases such as “Gam Siah”, “Relak Lah” and “Chiong Ah”. #RediscoveringSingapore #ExploringSingapore #RediscoverSG #ExploreSG #InterestingSingapore #FunInSingapore

#Foodporn: Thanks to a recommendation , I had the Pig's Trotters Lor Mee at the Singapore Food Festival - A Wok Down Memory Lane at Ellenborough Market.  I am normally not keen on Lor Mee and I've never had this combination but ....OMG!! Omg....it was THE BEST THING EVER! Not too starchy, the lor mee sauce was a mix of lor mee sauce and teh kar. Damm super duper shiokalicious decadently rich and so slurpy worthy! Look at the picture and you'll understand why I am raving about it! Highly recommended! Grateful for the recommendation friend! I ate it all up and went over to compliment them. Am aiming to go to their original stall to try one day. $6.50

post_caption: My to-go place for Vietnamese pho and I usually order their Bun Cha (grilled pork with dry noodles and sauce) or their soupy prawn and pork pho. They have customized to local tastes over the years and I thought they used to give raw veg. Still, their crispy spring rolls are addictive and decor shows the fabulous artistic qualities of Vietnamese.

Bussiness goes on. . . Earning a living after the circuit breaker. The last of Singapore’s streetside barber start his busssiness during the phase one.

Undying dedication to his trade and a master of the art, the one old-school barber. Streetside barbers used to be a thriving industry back then. Haircuts, and shave has been his passion for the last 56 years. A "A+" classic... .
.
Mr Lee is located behind Moosehead along Telok Ayer Street and he usually opens from 10.30am-4pm from Mon-Fri and 10.30am-3pm on Sat. To make an appointment, call him at 97712146. I am so wanting to try nostril hair trim 😄
.

Description
The temple is built in the ancient South Indian temple architectural style of the 7th-century Chola dynasty. The Chola dynasty is popular for some of the most beautiful and intricately carved temples, constructed during their reign, in India. The main tower entrance of the Sri Senpaga Vinayagar temple is a 21 m tall five-tier structure. The shrine of Lord Ganesha has a gold-plated dome. The teakwood door at the main entrance is 4.5 m high, keeping in mind that large doorways were required for kings who entered temples on Elephants. The temple's roof, topped by a dragon with images of many deities, was designed and carved by G. Radhakrishnan, a traditional temple architect in 1971. The colour scheme of the temple is terracotta and sandstone. Two newly added skylights allow both the Raja Gopuram, or the main tower and the Vimanam or the gold-plated main dome, to be seen from within the temple. In the 2500 sq m building, 32 forms of Vinayagar sculptures have been carved in granite on the four main pillars. 
The 120-year-old Sri Senpaga Vinayagar Temple in Ceylon Road had its consecration ceremony recently - the Maha Kumbhabishegam, a highly auspicious ritual held every 12 years.

It's been Refreshed, Revamped and Revitalised to better showcase Singapore's history from 700 years ago till present day. It's certainly a fresh look with lots of modern technology incorporated to make the visit more interesting, interactive and immersive. Opens to the public on Sat, Sept 19 with free entry and loads of fun activities for all.

The  new permanent galleries are  the Singapore History  Gallery,  the  Life in Singapore: The Past 100  Years galleries and the Goh Seng Choo Gallery.

At a major art fair with thousands of works, how do you stand out? This piece @sundaramtagore @artstagesg certainly caught my attention. The musical notes and sounds of a #Gamelan are unmistakable. The artist is Taylor Kuffner, and the work is called Mantera Hijau, 2014. 

More from his website:
The Gamelatron Project, draws on the thousand-year-old sonic tradition of Indonesia--Gamelan--and the emerging field of robotics to create magical, viscerally-powerful, site-specific performances and temporary and permanent installations.  The essence of the Gamelatron is in the live experience: Handcrafted, masterfully-tuned orchestras of vibraphones, drums, chimes, bells and resonating bronze gongs played by robotic mallets are installed to immerse the oberser in living kinetic sculptures. 

ART STAGE SINGAPORE
21 - 24 Jan, 12:00 PM - 6:00 PM

post_caption:
Yep I actually hobbled over with bandaged foot to see these cute #sg50moovecows from #moovemediaoutdoor . I do love them. They represent iconic characters from Singapore - here's
the Satay Man, the Wayang Opera Diva, the Samsui Woman, and the Coolie. "One of my favourite #SG50MooveCows is Samsui Woman because she help built Singapore. My hope for the future is a continual growing and prosperous Singapore." Info extracted Via Marketing:
Moove Media’s iconic cows can be seen all over the island in celebration of SG50.
The SG50 Moove cow, which stands at 1.76m each, will represent eight historical characters – the Coolie, the Rickshaw Man, the Kacang Puteh Man, the Satay Man, the domestic helper or “Ma Jie”, the Samsui Woman, the Nyonya as well as the Wayang Opera Diva.
The cows will also go on sale from 13 July onwards and proceeds from the sale will go towards the Home Improvement Fund that ComfortDelGro has set up to help improve the quality of living of the elderly of the Lions Befrienders Service Association (Singapore). #RediscoveringSingapore #ExploringSingapore #RediscoverSG #ExploreSG #InterestingSingapore #FunInSingapore

post_caption:
Provision shop in a home. 80-year-old Mr Ang is the key figure at Tee Seng Store and has been working here since 1955. Waking up at 5am everyday to practise qigong before opening his shop at 8am as he wants to stay get healthy so that he can continue to work here with his beloved wife.

He knows his regular what they want even before they asked. One of his customer shared the store has the biggest and fresh eggs.
An empty Milkmaid tin that was used to store cash in the past. Mr Ang now uses a scanner cash register.

What impressed me most was Mr Ang had learnt many languages  like Thai, Java, Tagalog, Malay, Tamil and Sinhala. He shared knowing these languages helps give that personal touch to the customers. Of course there's one language he wished to pick up and thats Jap. 

I am fortunate that Mr Ang allows me to take a shot of him and chat with his childhood days and all his experience since young till now and of course this kampung spirit and experience is something supermarket chains can never give you...
.
.
.
.
.
.

Saying a prayer for peace, luck and wealth at the temple has been a culture and ritual for many a Chinese during the Chinese New Year.  The  Kwan Im Thong Hood Cho Temple in Waterloo St is one popular temple where thousands of devotees flock to to offer prayers at the stroke of midnight on the first day of CNY.  Many youths today have also practised these intangible heritage of religious culture passed down for generations.

Trishaws were once the mode of transportation of choice in the 60s, 70s.  Be it a trip to the market or school, the trusty trishaw uncles would get us there rain or shine.  Today, trishaws are only retained for tourism purposes fetching tourist for sightseeing around the city. The pioneer and medeka generations will get that intangible nostalgic feel again riding a trishaw which many considered a transportation heritage.

Puddle Reflection
HDB Central Horizon

At HDB, the development of Selective En bloc Redevelopment Scheme (SERS) replacement projects to high standards of quality, design, and environmental innovation. As a result, many SERS replacement projects have won prestigious awards and accolades. These is just one of the examples.

The Development:

Block 79 Toa Payoh Central used to be a single 10-storey block. Today, the site is home to Central Horizon, a distinctive Toa Payoh landmark offering scenic panoramas of central Singapore.

HDB Central Horizon is made up of 5 towering 40-storey blocks, with a total of 1,158 units of 4-and 5-room flats.

The Honours:

• HDB Design Excellence Award 2008 (Housing Category)

• BCA Universal Design Award for Build Environment 2009 (Residential Building Category)

• SIA-NParks Skyrise Greenery Award 2009

#rediscoversg Tourism50
Reminisce #Singapore

Free guided tours of Haw Par Villa and talks, curated and conducted in English and Mandarin by local heritage tour specialist, Journeys. Learn about the history of Haw Par Villa and the brothers (businessmen Aw Boon Haw and Aw Boon Par) behind it, and delve into the Asian philosophy, values and beliefs that inspired the creation of the vivid sculptures and dioramas in the park.

The #Temple was beautifully lighted up tonight for the - Sri Mariamman’s Silver Chariot Procession 
Sri Mariamman Temple is the oldest Hindu temple in Singapore, dating back to 1827. The temple is dedicated to Goddess Mariamman, known for curing  illnesses and diseases.

post_caption:
"And in the naked light I saw
Ten thousand people, maybe more
People talking without speaking
People hearing without listening
People writing songs that voices never share
No one dare
Disturb the sound of silence . “Fools” said I, “You do not know
Silence like a cancer grows
Hear my words that I might teach you
Take my arms that I might reach you”
But my words like silent raindrops fell
And echoed in the wells of silence

And the people bowed and prayed
To the neon god they made
And the sign flashed out its warning
In the words that it was forming
And the sign said “The words of the prophets
Are written on the subway walls
And tenement halls
And whispered in the sounds of silence” "The Sound Of Silence" .

Negative Space w Willy.
•
Today we travel to Willy Wonker & his Chocolate Factory to talk about negative space.

•🍫 follow 📸 @gulajavatravelx 

We often hear about creating negative space and wonder what it is ? 
•
Simply put its creating black spaces in your photos and therein drawing the viewer’s eyes to the subject you are focusing on .
•
like in this photo, i have created dark spaces and used the light to focus on the mural of Willy Wonker.
•
whose your favourite Willy Wonker ? Gene Wilder or Johnny Depp ?

post_caption:
Some interesting highlights in the newly reopened (Sept 19) permanent galleries of the #NationalMuseumofSingapore : this
Type 95  Ha Go Japanese  #tank

Why? Cos Tom  Hanks  and  Steven  Spielberg touched it lah!

This replica  Type  95  Ha Go  was  the most  common Japanese tank  used in  World  War  Two and was  one  of  four  that  were  constructed  for  Tom  Hanks  and  Steven  Spielberg’s  television mini-series,  The  Pacific (2010). .............................................................. Had a sneak peek at the National Museum of Singapore's new Permanent galleries. It's been Refreshed, Revamped and Revitalised to better showcase Singapore's history from 700 years ago till present day. It's certainly a fresh look with lots of modern technology incorporated to make the visit more interesting, interactive and immersive. Opens to the public on Sat, Sept 19 with free entry and loads of fun activities for all.

The  new permanent galleries are  the Singapore History  Gallery,  the  Life in Singapore: The Past 100 Years galleries and the Goh Seng Choo Gallery.

"All colours 🌈 on a tree!" 

Eucalyptus deglupta is a species of tall tree, commonly known as the rainbow eucalyptus, Mindanao gum, or rainbow gum that is native to the Philippines, Indonesia, and Papua New Guinea.
The rainbow effect is created as the bark peels off throughout each season, revealing the fresh, bright-green bark below. As each layer of bark matures, it turns shades of blue, purple, orange, and red.

If you want to know exactly how the trees' bark becomes rainbow-hued, or to witness this beautiful rainbow eucalyptus trees, you are in luck. 

Here in Singapore, the one and only! 
The heritage Mindanao Gum Tree in Katong Park, Singapore.

.

夜幕降临，结束了忙碌的一天，让新加坡华乐团伴你放松心情，静下心来欣赏、细细品味琵琶首席俞嘉与古筝副首席许徽诠释唐代诗人张若虚的诗作《春江花月夜》的意境，作曲家艾立群因为阅读诗人陶渊明的五言诗篇《饮酒》而有感而发所创作的作品《悠然》，以及在二胡I首席赵剑华诠释下，唐代诗人李白的词作《忆秦娥》。意境空明、韵律宛转悠扬，回过神来，华乐团献上《台湾民谣三首》之《天黑黑》、《夜歌》，以及《夜深沉》等佳作，怡然自乐。点击 Bio链接购票！

post_caption:
Jubilee Walk Tour Point 9: Singapore River. Sir Stamford Raffles. 
The white polymarble statue of Raffles at the Singapore River is located at the historic Raffles Landing Site where Raffles was believed to first set foot on the island in 1819.
The statue is actually a copy of the original dark bronze statue, and was placed here in 1969 on the 150th anniversary of Singapore’s founding.
The original statue is just a short stroll away, in front of Victoria Memorial Hall at Empress Place. Sculpted by renowned Thomas Woolner, it was unveiled on Jubilee Day on 27 June 1887.

#Foodporn #Singapore #Indian #Food: One of the best #Chicken #Briyani around IMO. I brought a friend to eat at this neighbourhood stall and he loved it! The #bismatirice is unusually flavorful, tasty and aromatic. You can eat it on its own. 
Today we had the curry chicken with it but I like the fried chicken served with curry on the side. Huge portion for only $4.50 
From Wiki:
Biryani (pronounced [bɪr.jaːniː]) is a mixed rice dish from the Indian Subcontinent. It is made with spices, rice and meat or vegetables.

The spices and condiments used in biryani may include, but are not limited to, ghee(clarified butter), nutmeg, mace, pepper,cloves,[14] cardamom, cinnamon, bay leaves,coriander, mint leaves, ginger, onions, andgarlic. The premium varieties includesaffron.For a non-vegetarian biryani, the main ingredient that accompanies the spices is the meat, chicken and mutton. The dish may be served with dahi chutney or Raita,korma, curry, a sour dish of aubergine(brinjal), boiled egg, and salad.

post_caption:
"The National Heritage Board (NHB) gazetted Alkaff Upper Serangoon Mosque as the 68th National Monument in Singapore.

Opened in June 1932 by the Alkaffs, one of the prominent Arab families in Singapore, Alkaff Upper Serangoon Mosque is one of the two mosques established by the Alkaffs in the 1930s – the other being Alkaff Kampong Melayu Mosque. 
Designed by Swan & Maclaren, Alkaff Upper Serangoon Mosque boasts a unique blend of architectural styles. While the symmetrical layout of the prayer hall was influenced by the #Neoclassical style, its pencil-like minaret was borrowed from #Ottoman-Islamic architecture. In addition, the mosque features a hypostyle hall,1 which was prevalent in ancient Egyptian and Achaemenid (the Persian Empire, 550 – 330 B.C) architecture. A combination of Neoclassical Composite columns and #Moorish horseshoe arches can also be found in the main prayer hall and the side façade of the building." - Information extracted from NHB press release.

#WednesdayNightLaughter at the @thecomedyclubsg #SgComedyFringe #comedy show "SONS OF SINGAPORE" tonight - featuring the incomparably #Kumar who kept us hysterically laughing throughout with localised #jokes that were maybe politically incorrect but never offensive or insensitive. It's the special Kumar charm. He was clearly the crowd favourite.

Also appearing were Fakkah Fuzz, Rishi Budhrani and Jinx Yeo - 3 rising comedy stars ; a Malay, an Indian and a Chinese, representing the multi-racial make up of Singapore and jokes about Singaporeans. Fuzz was clearly the most experienced of the 3, Rishi was polished and Jinx seemingly the newbie of the group. They ranged from pretty good to oh oh.....that fell flat and was kinda insensitive but overall the audience was an appreciative lot and were kept laughing and cheering throughout.

Pity the "SONS OF SINGAPORE"  is one night only - the full house certainly testified to the enduring popularity and draw of Kumar and company. 
The Singapore 2015 Comedy Fringe plays till Saturday 13th June with 6 more sets of #comedians from different countries. Catch one - #laughter is really the best medicine ! http://www.thecomedyclub.asia/home/

Photography through conceptualization and visualization. 🤔

Camera gears are just tools to make images. We have to change the mindset to work with our available tools and make the best out of it instead of acquiring new gears or getting the latest gears📸. 

Here in this overly shared and posted viewpoint of the newly open Apple store in MBS, I wanted something different and unusual, I visualize how nice it is to have a projection of Apple 🍎logo. I tried and tested some shots and finally I made this shot through the use of variable focal length within a long exposure. It is fun to explore and achieve results that you have crafted up in our mind. Change your perspective and it could change what your your end result would be 😊.
Enjoy the process and not the result! Be the change... in the mindset 😊
.
.

House of Tan Teng Niah -View 1
#sg_photocommunity #sgig #stb_sg #architecture #architecturephotography #architecture_hunter #colorful #vintage #singaporephotos #singapore #history #art #culture #traditionalart  #rediscoversg #orientphotocontest2020 #orientfoto 

THIS VIVIDLY COLORFUL HOUSE WAS constructed in 1900 by a local businessman named Tan Teng Niah. At the time, the neighborhood was an industrial zone (Tan’s candy and rubber factories were located nearby) and many of Singapore’s ethnic-Chinese businessmen lived in similar villas.
Amid Singapore’s rapid economic growth and social change during the 20th century, the neighborhood evolved into what is now known as Little India. Most of the old merchant houses were razed to make way for modern commercial buildings and sleek skyscrapers. However, the Tan Teng Niah house survived, and during the 1980s, it underwent a full restoration to what people see today.

Smile ❤️ because you only have one life to do it. Don’t live everyday in sadness.

#sg_photocommunity #sgig #stb_sg #architecture #architecturephotography #architecture_hunter #colorful #vintage #singaporephotos #singapore #history #art #culture #traditionalart #rediscoversg #orientphotocontest2020 #orientfoto

I love them all, these #sg50moovecows by #moovemediaoutdoor made me smile. Yep ....#nostelgia #memories . The Nonya reminds me of all the Peranakan ladies in my life, especially my nanny and I love that this is featured with a #tinkat ....cos that means food right? She was a wonderful cook and was always beautifully groomed and dressed elegantly in her sarong kebaya.  I loved seeing her getting all dressed up, it was a process, and then taking care of her hair and powdering her face. "One of my favourite #SG50MooveCows is Nyonya lady because it reminds me of my Peranakan nanny and granny. My hope for the future is one where the Peranakan culture still flourishes." Info extracted Via Marketing:
Moove Media’s iconic cows can be seen all over the island in celebration of SG50.
The SG50 Moove cow, which stands at 1.76m each, will represent eight historical characters – the Coolie, the Rickshaw Man, the Kacang Puteh Man, the Satay Man, the domestic helper or “Ma Jie”, the Samsui Woman, the Nyonya as well as the Wayang Opera Diva.
The cows will also go on sale from 13 July onwards and proceeds from the sale will go towards the Home Improvement Fund that ComfortDelGro has set up to help improve the quality of living of the elderly of the Lions Befrienders Service Association (Singapore). #RediscoveringSingapore #ExploringSingapore #RediscoverSG #ExploreSG #InterestingSingapore #FunInSingapore

160 BY PIERRE & JOËL RODIÈRE / TRAFIK, PRODUCTION BY TETRO
Viewing times: 7pm to 10pm (28 & 29 Oct); 7pm to 11pm (30 & 31 Oct). 160 is an interactive light and sound installation consisting of 160 light bars covering an area of about 60 meters. The public can take ownership of the space by playing with the light and sound to create a visually stimulating and sensory experience. View from HDB City Vue @ Henderson

At City Vue @ Henderson, you will discover plenty of recreational options that cater to the residents of all ages. Children will enjoy playing at the children’s playgrounds. Fitness enthusiasts can stretch their muscles at the adult and elderly fitness stations, or engage in games at the hard courts. Those who wish to gather with the neighbours for a friendly chat can do so at the resting shelters and precinct pavilions. The roof garden above the multi-storey carpark will provide an ideal spot for quiet contemplation or an evening stroll.

Located at the junction of Tiong Bahru Road and Henderson Road, City Vue @ Henderson is sited close to Tiong Bahru MRT station and Tiong Bahru Plaza.

This development comprises 5 residential blocks ranging from 27, 40 and 48 storeys public housing flats. There are total of 1,232 units of 2-, 3-, 4- and 5-room Standard Flats.

The name City-Vue @ Henderson reflects its prime location close to the city.

Beautiful Fullerton having the 夜上海 feel. 
One of the most iconic building in Singapore dating back to Colonial days. 

The Fullerton Hotel Singapore is a five-star luxury hotel located near the mouth of the Singapore River, in the Downtown Core of the Central Area, Singapore. It was originally known as the Fullerton Building, and also as the General Post Office Building. The address is 1 Fullerton Square. The Fullerton Building was named after Robert Fullerton, the first Governor of the Straits Settlements (1826–1829).

At the beach

Stroll through the colourful enclaves of Joo Chiat/Katong, home to hipster cafés, historical shophouses and Peranakan culture.  Immerse into the beautiful culture,  blend of old and new. Family businesses and quaint shophouses sit alongside cool cafés and hip boutiques.

Alongside the walls, the beautifully painted mural art will wow you and selfie worthy. 

Most of the murals here are a result of the Katong Joo Chiat Art Circuit ( #KJCArtCircuit ) organised by The Admin SG – same folk who set up Gelam Gallery in the back alleys of Kampong Glam – and commissioned by the Singapore Tourism Board to revitalise this area.
