Displaying Polaroid photographs of personalities such as Warhol himself, Bianca Jagger, Andre Leon Talley, Tina Chow and Martha Graham, ANDY WARHOL: Social Circus pays homage to Warhol’s iconic studio, The Factory, and avant-garde New York life. post_caption:
#Foodporn #Singapore #Chinese : the other #foodstall I introduced to my friend was one ran by a nice Chinese couple. Their #xiaolongbao is really good. Only $4 for half a dozen! Cheap and very good. 
From Wiki: 
Xiaolongbao is a type of steamed bun (baozi) from the Jiangnan region of China, especially associated with Shanghai and Wuxi. It is traditionally prepared in xiaolong, small bamboo steaming baskets, which give them their name. 
Xiaolongbao are traditionally filled with pork. One popular and common variant is pork with minced crab meat and roe. More modern innovations include other meats, seafood and vegetarian fillings, as well as other possibilities. The characteristic soup-filled kind are created by wrapping solid meat aspicinside the skin alongside the meat filling. Heat from steaming then melts the gelatin-gelled aspic into soup.

post_caption:
Visitors to the #SingaporeYuHuangGong will be greeted by a pair of dragons at the entrance and a newly replaced imperial treasure gourd at the top of a three-storey pagoda. ..................................................................This little gem of a #Taoist #temple on Telok Ayer Street was kept hidden for over a hundred years. This is the national #monument, the Singapore 'Yu Huang Gong', Temple of The Heavenly Jade Emperor, located at 150 Telok Ayer Streer. Extensive restoration work was undertaken last few years to save the historic 170-year-old temple and has now been completed.

post_caption: Daily routine

Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
@ Leong Nam Temple 
龍南殿九皇大二帝爷圣诞 
Rain or shine...devotees come in drove to offer prayers to the Nine Emperor Gods.
The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia. 
Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. Today, the younger generations have taken an interest in the festival, with many youths taking part in the processions. Involving the younger generations allows us to continue this intangible cultural heritage for many generations to come.

HDB Central Horizon

At HDB, the development of Selective En bloc Redevelopment Scheme (SERS) replacement projects to high standards of quality, design, and environmental innovation. As a result, many SERS replacement projects have won prestigious awards and accolades. These is just one of the examples.

The Development:

Block 79 Toa Payoh Central used to be a single 10-storey block. Today, the site is home to Central Horizon, a distinctive Toa Payoh landmark offering scenic panoramas of central Singapore.

HDB Central Horizon is made up of 5 towering 40-storey blocks, with a total of 1,158 units of 4-and 5-room flats.

The Honours:

• HDB Design Excellence Award 2008 (Housing Category)

• BCA Universal Design Award for Build Environment 2009 (Residential Building Category)

• SIA-NParks Skyrise Greenery Award 2009

post_caption:
I wanted to rescue this little bird's nest fern I saw growing out of a drainage pipe. I actually contemplates climbing over the parapet walls! Yep #thatcrazy #birdsnestfern
............................................................... Once 669 families lived in Blocks 74 to 80 at Commonwealth Drive. They were also known as Chap Lau Chu : 10-storey houses in Hokkien. The area is also known as Tanglin Halt, where some of the earliest HDB flats are to be found. The 7 blocks had been identified for redevelopment under Sers and residents moved out to new 40 story flats, nearby. Soon these flats from a bygone era will be demolished.

Today it held its farewell party "Goodbye 74 to 80 Commonwealth Drive" organised by My Queenstown.

Double Rainbow over The Pinnacle @ Duxton HDB. What a beautiful view of the city from my neighbourhood at HDB Kim Tian Green. In this neighbourhood, there are seven blocks of 40 storey tall HDB public housing flats. Every flats have different breathtaking view of the city, ports, towns and nearby islands too. Sometimes, we may get to see rainbow in the morning or in the late afternoon just after the rain. Whenever I saw one in the sky, I will inform my neighbours so that they will not miss seeing the beautiful colours of the rainbow. And I quickly grab my camera and tripod, take the lift up to the highest floor to capture this amazing double rainbows over the city.

HDB Kim Tian Green:

Kim Tian Green have Blk 126A, 126B, 126C, 127A, 127B, 127C & 127D at Kim Tian Road are 40 storey HDB public housing flats in Bukit Merah, District 03, Singapore. It has a total of 214 units with 78 units of 3-room unit type and 136 units of 4-room unit type in every block. These flats were completed in 2011 and has a 90 years lease remaining. Kim Tian Green, Blk 126c, Kim Tian Road is located near Tiong Bahru Mrt Station (Ew17).

The French artist behind The Little Prince exhibition,  Arnaud Nazare-Aga of Artheline PAJ Art Studio, who was behind two world-premiere art exhibitions in Singapore which were presented by the Antoine de Saint-Exupéry Youth Foundation as part of the French cultural festival, Voilah!, organized by the French Embassy and Institut Français in Singapore. 
The artist has an interesting backstory which fascinated me - he actually joined a Tibetan Buddhist monastery in Burgundy and was there for 13 years and was also involved in the building of the first Himalayan temple in the West! It seems he's also an ordained lama - fascinating personal story right? 
He only officially started on his current occupation, as an artist
 just 5 years ago, proving it's never too late in life to start a second career - provided one has the talent like he has of course!

post_caption:
If you don’t reside around the area, you might not be familiar with East Village mall, right opposite Simpang Bedok. Though it isn’t big in space, the variety of food choices available is not small either! 

Yummy Takoyaki
@yummytakoyaki offers halal takoyaki flavours you never thought could exist such as Nutella Takoyaki ($15/10pcs) and Cheese Banjir Takoyaki ($15/10pcs). Banjir translates to “flood” so you can imagine the amount of cheese just oozing out of that takoyaki!

📍 430 Upper Changi Road, #01-61 East Village, Singapore 487048

Hoho Chimek
Craving for fried chicken after bingeing on your k-dramas? Head down to @hohochimek for their Soy Garlic Korean Fried Chicken Wings (from $9.90)! They also have other dishes such as Budaejjigae ($15).

📍 430 Upper Changi Road, #01-45 East Village, Singapore 487048

Terang Bulan
@terangbulansg serves up authentic martabak manis, which is a thick sweet pancake originating from Indonesia. Fans of Min Chiang Kueh will definitely love this due to its similarity. For $10, you can get the Party Box that allows you to choose 4 flavours - 2 premium and 2 standard.

Terang Bulan has recently moved out from East Village but they are still open for business through their website for delivery!

Chulop!
Churros from @chulopsg is the perfect after-meal snack! The cherry on top of this snack that’s already lip-smacking good by itself is the local touch that Chulop has added to their Pandan Churros paired with a Gula Melaka dip ($5/4pcs).

📍 430 Upper Changi Rd, #01-59, Singapore 487048

Hong Kong Street Family Restaurant
You can’t go wrong with zi char, it’s popular with all ages! Order a hearty and milky bowl of Fish Head Bee Hoon Soup ($6-$17) to share with your family or chomp down on their popular Prawn Sauce Chicken ($10-$20)!

📍 430 Upper Changi Road, #01-67/68 East Village, Singapore 487048

Here's my 15 minutes of fame - the old fashion selfie #polaroid ! 

The most popular happening at the happening #AndyWarholSocialCircus party by #TheRyanFoundation was the #polaroid corner. Before there were selfish and Instagram, #AndyWarhol had his ever present Polaroid camera with which he took ultra glamorous shots of the most famous and beautiful celebrities of the day. 

The Ryan Foundation presents: ANDY WARHOL: Social Circus.

Displaying Polaroid photographs of personalities such as Warhol himself, Bianca Jagger, Andre Leon Talley, Tina Chow and Martha Graham, ANDY WARHOL: Social Circus pays homage to Warhol’s iconic studio, The Factory, and avant-garde New York life. Warhol's Polaroids could also be among the first "selfies".

post_caption: 17/12/16 Earliest memory of coffee was from the local coffee shops in the neighbourhood of Lavender. The scent of Robusta beans caramelised with butter and sugar evoke recollections of a childhood running around the void decks, passing kopitiams (coffee shops) where the cookie aroma of kopi (coffee) lingered in the air. New hipster cafes have since moved into the neighbourhood, but a trip back to the vicinity is always a precious chance to visit for kopi 'guyou' (butter), the local version of bulletproof coffee. The tiles on the wall are stained with age, echoing the elderly owner who still serves up the occasional cup for regulars in his striped pyjama pants. His son has since taken over, pouring out cups of nostalgia for different generations of patrons seeking to relive the days where time moved slowly and drinks were still stirred and sipped without haste.

Completed the day of food discovery with dinner at Maggie Joan’s, literally a hidden gem entered via the dark alley of Gemmill Lane; by the folks from Moose Head at Telok Ayer. It’s fine cuisine in a chic-casual setting, dimly lit with bare brick walls,  and even miniature  chandeliers. Helmed by British head chef, Oliver Hyde,  who had done time at Waterside Inn and Restaurant Gordon Ramsay in London; and Pollen in Singapore. All the food was beautifully plated: Garlic and rosemary-speckled bread with hummus; Deep fried and dukkah-dusted slow-poached #egg with yolk-like saffron mayo; Heirloom tomatoes, compress peach, burrata, tapenade; the Yellowtail #sashimi, carrot escabeche, brandade; and the Hokkaido #scallop carpaccio, peas, Iberico paleta. The main of Bangers strip-loin was perfectly charred medium rare in the Inka oven.  Comes with a price tag but worth splurging for that special occasion  #yoursingapore #interestingsingapore #igsg #artists #rediscoversg  #sgig  #rediscoveringsingapore #sg50 #arts #jj_editors #igsingapore #exploringsingapore #glitzglamour #maggiejoans #singaporeinsiders #sgfood #sgfoodblogger

post_caption:
A compilation of the beautiful house of Tan Teng Niah; 
Built in 1900, the former house of Tan Teng Niah is the last surviving Chinese villa in Little India. Tan Teng Niah was a towkay (Chinese businessman of good standing) Many believe that Tan built the house for his wife and that the inscription referred to her. The design of the house were beautifully crafted including the main door inscription made just for his wife. Note of the blossom flowers on the windows. The former house of Tan Teng Niah has eight rooms.

To the Chinese, the house design was auspiciously designed. Each doorway was beautifully decorated with carvings including the twirling wooden stairway of the golden dragons which impressed me most. The carvings were so detailed, precise and elegantly designed. Kudos to the 1900s skillful carpenters. 

The house was restored and conserved in the 1980s for commercial use, and the restoration project was awarded the Singapore Institute of Architects Honourable Mention in 1991. It is partially rented out Mr Chandran who had been there for more than 10years. He is a retired police officer whom set up this flower bussiness. I  was fortunate to have him sharing of his experiences and allowing me to take the beautiful interior of the villa.

The 2nd of the 3 #exhibitions under #SingaporeHeritageFest , at the National Museum, that's ending this week, that is worth going to is : 
Moderns in Our Midst: A Photographic Tribute to Singapore's Modern Architectural Heritage
It showcases Singapore's early architectural style and is a great look as some of them are no longer around. This picture shows the original Collyer Quay

Moderns in Our Midst: A Photographic Tribute to Singapore's Modern Architectural Heritage
Concourse, Level 1
17 Apr 2015 - 18 May 2015
10am - 6pm
Free admission

Taken over a span of ten years, these photographs by award-winning architectural photographer, the late Jeremy San Tzer Ning (1976-2013), represent a passionate, ambitious and wide-ranging undertaking to capture Singapore’s endangered early Modernist architecture.

#chalk #candles #vintage #schooldays
................................................... Had a sneak peek at the National Museum of Singapore's new Permanent galleries. It's been Refreshed, Revamped and Revitalised to better showcase Singapore's history from 700 years ago till present day. It's certainly a fresh look with lots of modern technology incorporated to make the visit more interesting, interactive and immersive. Opens to the public on Sat, Sept 19 with free entry and loads of fun activities for call.
The  new permanent  galleries are  the  Singapore History  Gallery,  the  Life  in  Singapore: The Past  100  Years  galleries  and the  Goh  Seng Choo  Gallery.

post_caption:
Jubilee Walk Tour Point 9 and 10: @acm_sg Asian Civilisation museum on the Singapore River. 
The Singapore River is the birthplace of modern Singapite and commerce flourished along the wharves and immigrant communities settled close to the banks. Singapore’s first land reclamation project took place here in the 1820s, when the river’s swampy south bank was converted into what are now Boat Quay and Raffles Place.

post_caption:
Already gone to all the food places we recommended in our Bedok edition last week? Well, we are back with a brand new area to explore – Changi! Besides being home to the world’s best airport, there’s also plenty of hidden food gems to discover. 

Little Island Brewing Company
Fun fact! Did you know that Singapore has our very own microbrewery? @littleislandbrew offers locally-brewed craft beers alongside scrumptious bites such as Slow Roasted Pork Belly ($26) for you to enjoy with your loved ones under a starry sky.

📍6 Changi Village Road, S(509907)

Chock Full Of Beans
For a unique cafe experience, head down to @chockfullofbeans for their 2D and 3D latte art ($7.5-$8) specially designed by their baristas. Good things come to those who wait so do ensure that you have ample time as the 3D latte art requires up to 30mins wait time!

📍Blk 4 Changi Village Road #01-2090, S(500004)

Ikura Singapore
To satiate your wanderlust during this pandemic period, visit @ikura_sg for an authentic Japanese izakaya experience. Have a drink while enjoying Ikura’s extensive menu that offers yakitori ($1-$3.5) and sushi ($2-$20).

📍 430 Upper Changi Road, #01-01, East Village S(487048)

The Coastal Settlement
Transport yourself to olden days Singapore with @thecoastalsettlement’s unique interior featuring vintage and antique decor. Indulge in an Indonesian Duck Confit ($34) and Ribeye Mac & Cheese ($41) in the old Changi Military Base area.

📍200, Netheravon Road, S(508529)

Changi Village Hawker Centre
With hawkers being an integral part of Singapore’s culture, no area would be complete without one! Must-try food include Weng Kee Ipoh Hor Fun ($3.5/$5) and Nasi Lemak ($3.5) from International Muslim Food Stall and Mizzy Corner Nasi Lemak.

📍 2 Changi Village Road, #01-18/19, #01-03, #01-26 Changi Village Hawker Centre, S(500002)

post_caption:
【必去新加坡的小土耳其｜著街區太迷人了】

19世紀法國軍事家拿破侖曾說：「如果世界是一個國家，它的首都一定會是伊斯坦堡。」 19世紀的法國詩人拉馬丁則在遊歷過伊斯坦堡後說：「如果只能看這個世界一眼，那就看伊斯坦堡吧！」
	
橫跨兩大洲與博斯普魯斯海峽的伊斯坦堡，舊名為「君士坦丁堡」，曾是羅馬帝國、拜佔庭帝國與鄂圖曼帝國的首都，如今更是土耳其共和國的第一大城。
	
如此迷人的地方究竟是怎樣的？雖然今年前去土耳其🇹🇷旅遊的計劃泡湯了，我在新加坡甘榜格南(Kampong Glam 穆斯林的聚居區）的Bussorah street 巴梭拉街貌似找到了答案～這條街如同是個濃縮迷你版的土耳其🥰
	
💁‍♀️在Bussorah street（通常也有人會籠統地稱這裡為Arab street）除了可以打卡新加坡著名的回教堂Sultan Mosque，還可以近距離感受到帶著古拜佔庭與鄂圖曼元素的土耳其風情。61Bussorah street是間迷你版的grand bazaar 大巴扎，擺滿了繽紛多彩的鄂圖曼風格的馬薩克玻璃燈，也能看到用伊茲尼克磁磚做的的鍋碗瓢盆～都很喜歡！
💁‍♀️有美美的工藝品當然也少不了各種地中海風味和土耳其的美食。我第一次吃到有著舉世聞名土耳其「pizza」之稱的pide，烤肉拼盤和蘋果茶就在著兒🥰
💁‍♀️bussorah street是我很喜歡這個地方，無限回返！各種民族風的東西和美食都可以在這裡找到～之前寫的halal北歐烘培坊也在著哦～也有Arabica% 咖啡館。祝大家天天開心～下集我再多寫寫這裡的土耳其甜點和咖啡，和逛中東地攤之旅！

#Door #graffiti of a #Samsui #woman - the original superwoman and feminist before these concepts even exist. They came over from China to work on construction sites in Singapore, carrying heavy loads across their shoulders like a weighing scale. They were dressed in a distinctive headgear and blue samfoo, frequently staying single. "Chamber of God" by Mujahidin Nurrahman @artstagesg D4

I stumbled across this beautiful and thought provoking piece by talented Bandung artist Mujahidin Nurrahman as I was leaving #ArtStageSg. I spent the most time checking out the gorgeous installation piece and was lucky to hear the story behind the inspiration for Chambers of God. The installation art piece was borne out of the Artist's desire to discuss the issue of war and conflict in the Middle East, how the world sees Islam and Muslims and includes a tie back to World War UK in the form of old photos and gas mask found in the flea markets of Paris. He painstakingly cut out the intricate Arabesque patterns on the screen and canvases. Go check it out if you're there. I thought it would be great for the Singapore Biennial actually. 

ART STAGE SINGAPORE
21 - 24 Jan, 12:00 PM - 6:00 PM
Marina Bay Singapore

post_caption:
The good old days at Tee Seng Store. Putting everything together, hope u like it...

Provision shop in a home. 80-year-old Mr Ang is the key figure at Tee Seng Store and has been working here since 1955. Waking up at 5am everyday to practise qigong before opening his shop at 8am as he wants to stay get healthy so that he can continue to work here with his beloved wife.

He knows his regular what they want even before they asked. One of his customer shared the store has the biggest and fresh eggs.
An empty Milkmaid tin that was used to store cash in the past. Mr Ang now uses a scanner cash register.

What impressed me most was Mr Ang had learnt many languages  like Thai, Java, Tagalog, Malay, Tamil and Sinhala. He shared knowing these languages helps give that personal touch to the customers. Of course there's one language he wished to pick up and thats Jap. 

I am fortunate that Mr Ang allows me to take a shot of him and chat with his childhood days and all his experience since young till now and of course this kampung spirit and experience is something supermarket chains can never give you...

House of Tan Teng Niah -View 2
#sg_photocommunity #sgig #stb_sg #architecture #architecturephotography #architecture_hunter #colorful #vintage #singaporephotos #singapore #history #art #culture #traditionalart  #rediscoversg #orientphotocontest2020 #orientfoto 

THIS VIVIDLY COLORFUL HOUSE WAS constructed in 1900 by a local businessman named Tan Teng Niah. At the time, the neighborhood was an industrial zone (Tan’s candy and rubber factories were located nearby) and many of Singapore’s ethnic-Chinese businessmen lived in similar villas.
Amid Singapore’s rapid economic growth and social change during the 20th century, the neighborhood evolved into what is now known as Little India. Most of the old merchant houses were razed to make way for modern commercial buildings and sleek skyscrapers. However, the Tan Teng Niah house survived, and during the 1980s, it underwent a full restoration to what people see today.

History of Little Guilin (小桂林）

Together with the neighbouring Bukit Batok Nature Park, Bukit Batok Town Park occupies 77 hectares of land in Bukit Batok planning area, which covers the subzones Bukit Gombak, Hong Kah, Brickworks and Hillview. The park was a granite quarry for extracting a form of norite called Gombak norite. The name of the area, Bukit Batok, which means "coughing hills", was derived from the sounds of quarrying activities.

When the granite had to be extracted below sea level and could threaten the ecology of the area, the government closed down the quarries in Bukit Batok and made arrangements to purchase granite from Indonesia instead. As a result, the quarry became abandoned and rainwater filled it up over time, turning it into a mini lake. In 1984, the Housing and Development Board (HDB) wanted to fill up the quarry and build a road over it. However, after seeing that the existing quarry had rugged granite outcrops and a contrasting backdrop of green hills that gave it a pleasant look, the HDB converted the quarry into a park instead. They also beautified the surroundings and improved accessibility by placing granite blocks on the retaining walls, as well as adding footpaths, lights and seating. The park was called "Little Guilin" or "Xiao Guilin" by the locals because the granite formations resemble the mountains in Guilin in China's Guangxi Province.

The #SingaporeYuHuangGong. temple was in need of extensive repairs and restorations and was in a fragile state. A team of craftsmen, including sculptors from Quanzhou, in the southern Fujian province of China, were brought in to work on the interiors. ................................................................This little gem of a #Taoist #temple on Telok Ayer Street was kept hidden for over a hundred years. This is the national #monument, the Singapore 'Yu Huang Gong', Temple of The Heavenly Jade Emperor, located at 150 Telok Ayer Streer. Extensive restoration work was undertaken last few years to save the historic 170-year-old temple and has now been completed.

post_caption:
Cool weather and rain throughout the day. 
Alighted one stop before my place to capture this beautiful school with rich history.

History of CCHS. 

With the start of enrolment of female students by Chung Cheng High School in 1947, student population increased significantly throughout the post war years, and the initial premise of the school at River Valley became increasingly overcrowded. In August 1947, Lin Shi Wan, Chairman of the Management Board, set up a new campus on a plot of land at Goodman Road, naming the campus Chung Cheng High School (Main) while the original school at Kim Yam road functioned as a branch school, renamed as Chung Cheng High School (Branch).[3]

In May 1969, the School Management Committee of Chung Cheng High School and The Singapore Hokkien Huay Kuan agreed on an exchange of campus land of Chung Cheng High School (Branch) with a newly built Kong Hwa Wing building adjacent to Kong Hwa School. Chung Cheng High (Branch) was relocated to 339 Guillemard Road, while the original premises at 60 Kim Yam Rd becoming part of the extension for the campus of Nan Chiau Girls' High School.[4] In 1981, following unification of language streams by the Ministry of education, the school began to convert to English stream classes. In the late 1980s, there was an urgent need to upgrade the school facilities and to move to a spacious location. As rebuilding the school on the current 0.6 hectare land was not feasible, the school opted for relocation to a more spacious better-equipped facility.[3][5]

Between January 2002 and 2005, the school operated at two campuses, the Guillemard site and the holding school at Sembawang Drive.[6] Chung Cheng High School (Branch) was renamed as Chung Cheng High School (Yishun) with effect from January 2006.[6]

post_caption:
Mama Zi making pathiri roti or varuthamavu roti. 

Audio on here and you can see baby T asking all the questions on how it's made, why it's made this way and how to make it with little resources. 

All this needs is rice flour, salt, water and coocnut. This was a dish, mama zi said was one that she made with her mum for funerals and 'pathiyas' (funeral prayers). It was an easy dish that took little time and made in batches for those who came to pray. 

These days, we make it for normal dinners too 😊

#Foodporn #Jelly #AgarAgar 
How #cute right! A neighbour made this in place of a came for her father for Father's Day - I love it! #Nature #Garden #Butterflies #BumbleBee theme! So clever!

post_caption: #rediscoversg #whatmakessg #mysingapore #pekkio

@pastariaabateitalian , very very delicious homemade pasta!

[$$. ✨✨✨]

1.Lobster Pasta with Lemon Butter Sauce

When Sistar first saw the lobster, sis legs turn jelly. Lucky Sistar sitting in chair if not sis will be the 3rd lobster on the plate. Mr Lobster was huge and very fresh! Mr L tiny bit salty for sis but paired very well with the lemon butter sauce.

2.Truffle Carbonara

Homemade Spaghetti was QQ de, the truffle carbonara sauce was 👍. Sis open eyes hoping she in Italy, but she saw her Singaporean bf beside her. No macho hairy chest, no blonde hair 😒. 

3. Fried Mozarella

All Sis can say is that Sis can pull the cheese from Pasir ris to Jurong.

4.Homemade Pannacotta with Fruity Sauce

Pannacotta was smooth, light and creamy, homemade too! The berry sauce added a refreshing taste.

This one Sistar give stamp for approval that all Sistars must go!!! If don't go cannot join Sistarhood.

Every corner is an IG-worthy spot, and the service of the western lady staff is top notch. Breads are your best bet here (come for breakfast or simply ask for whatever breads they have during dinner - I got a small bag of heavenly baguettes). post_caption:
Thaipusam in Singapore: "Kavadi means "sacrifice at every step". The act of carrying the kavadi is the most distinctive act during Thaipusam. Lemons on metal hooks are hooked directly onto the bodies of the men. They are also pierced with other sharp objects. The kavadi is typcically made of aluminium, and covered with coloured and peacock feathers, with the symbol of Lord Murugan at the top. Kavadis can reach three to four metres in height, and weigh at least 30kgs. Kavadi bearers generally report that they do not feel pain while carrying the structures, as they are in a spiritual trance. "

In association with Soorya (Singapore)
20 & 21 Nov 2015 : 7.30pm & 9pm

Outdoor Theatre

With roots dating back to 17th century northern Kerala, Krishnattam is an all-male temple dance drama that tells the story of Lord Krishna over a series of eight plays. Created by Manaveda, the Zamorin raja (king) of Calicut, in 1653, the play is performed today only at the temple dedicated to Lord Krishna in the town of Guruvayoor.

#Foodporn : Tonight was a #tb flashback in time for me when we dined at the Goldleaf Restaurant which has been in operation since 1971! They serve #Teochew #Porridge accompanied by a menu of over 60 items; a lot of them reminiscent of good our mother's and grandmothers cooked for us when we were young. #ComfortFood essentially. I used to patronized in when I was a teen and in my 20s, when we would go after the clubs and discos closed! 
Tonight I asked for the traditional #food items , so we had - sweet potatoe porridge with chai poh omelette, long beans, minced meat with salted fish, bean curd with pork floss and salted eggs. It was such a #nostalgic moment for me, remembering the tastes and the memory of my youth eating these comfort food.

#Sg50Food #SgHeritageFood #Foodporn : Good cooked over charcoal stoves and in claypots reminds me of childhood, my grandma and nanny who slaved for hours over a small charcoal stove, fanning the flames as the food cooks slowly in a #claypot . Food cooked in claypot tastes different, infused with the flavour of the much used claypot and the charcoal flavour. I still remember the first time my mum cooked frog's legs for me. I was apprehensive but loved it instantly. One of the best around....Eminent Frog's Legs Porridge....this was the Kung Pao version with dried chillie and thick rich sauce and heaped with spring onions. It was super #shiok.  #SG50Makan #Foodporn #local #Singaporean #hawker #HawkerFood #traditional #Froglegs

Visitors to the #SingaporeYuHuangGong will be greeted by a pair of dragons at the entrance and a newly replaced imperial treasure gourd at the top of a three-storey pagoda. ............................................. ......................This little gem of a #Taoist #temple on Telok Ayer Street was kept hidden for over a hundred years. This is the national #monument, the Singapore 'Yu Huang Gong', Temple of The Heavenly Jade Emperor, located at 150 Telok Ayer Streer. Extensive restoration work was undertaken last few years to save the historic 170-year-old temple and has now been completed.

#SG50Food #Foodporn Walking into this traditional confectionery shop that looked nondescript from the outside was like walking back into my childhood. I chance upon it and lucked on them just bringing out trays of freshly baked peanut candy. It smelled....oh so good! The fresh smell of quality seasame baked with roasted peanuts and sugar and honey.....lovely to bite into. The smell was of childhood and nanny and grandma cooking, of indulging in candies and games. Heavenly. You cannot find fresh baked peanut candies like these anymore. They're all factory baked and taste a pale imitation.

#Monkeys here there everywhere! That's how you know which Chinese Zodiac Year it is! The Festive Street Bazaar & Festive Carnival starts 15 Jan to 7 Feb 2016 - I make yearly trips to soak in the atmosphere! 
Chinese: 猴 hóu
Years of the Monkey: 1920, 1932, 1944, 1956, 1968, 1980, 1992, 2004, 2016, 2028
The monkey is a clever animal. It is usually compared to a smart person. During the Spring and Autumn Period (770 - 476 BC), the dignified Chinese official title of marquis was pronounced 'Hou', the same as the pronunciation of ‘monkey’ in Chinese. The animal was thereby bestowed with an auspicious meaning.
(travelchinaguide.com)

post_caption:
📍Switilicious Bakes⁣⁣
⁣⁣
These baklava rings from @switiliciousbakes score a 10/10 in presentation and 10/10 in taste. I tried the regular sized baklava rings, each of which can be finished in two bites, making for a tasty mid-day snack. Imagine a buttery, flaky pastry base, topped with a rich, chocolaty filling (there are 4 fillings, white chocolate, milk chocolate, nutella, and biscoff), finished with a sprinkle of pistachios, oreo, or biscoff - that’s what you get with each of these carefully handcrafted baklava rings. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
p.s. @switiliciousbakes are currently running a giveaway, do check out their account to find out how you can win yourself a box of 16 regular sized baklava rings! ⁣
⁣
p.p.s this picture features a jar of osmanthus honey from @bigboyschixsg, who so kindly allowed me to use their honey to further beautify this lovely setup. check out their account to find out more about their osmanthus honey and other honey products!

Everyone understood good food took time to prepare. We waited patiently for a traditional taste of Bak Chor Mee, cooked for each individual , not mass or rushed: 
#SG50Food #SG50Makan #Foodporn:
One creation locally born, infused with mixed origins, is Bak Chor Mee. #traditionalfood #heritagefood 
Chinatown Smith Street Food Centre #02-023 by "Teochew Street Mushroom Minced Meat Noodle" 
According to Hungry Go Where: 
Bak chor mee means “minced meat noodle” in #Teochew.
Like char kway teow and chwee kueh, bak chor mee is a uniquely Singaporean street food created by early Teochew immigrants. The original version was a soup dish, using mee pok–a type of flat egg noodle. Later, the dry version—noodles tossed in a piquant mix of chilli, vinegar, and lard oil—became more popular.
Of all the elements required for a superb bowl of bak chor mee, the trickiest part is the noodles.

Today I visited the Alkaff Upper Serangoon Mosque for a tour followed by Iftar under the Celebrate Monuments! organised by Preservation of Sites and Monuments under the National Heritage Board. This was the Iftar meal at the end of our tour, nasi lemak with dates, kueh, hot tea and watermelon #shiok 
Via Wiki:
Iftar (Arabic: إفطار‎ ifṭār 'breakfast') is the evening meal when Muslims end their daily Ramadan fast at sunset.
For Sunnis, it is at the time of the call to prayer for the evening prayer; for Shias, it is after the evening prayer.
Iftar is one of the religious observances of Ramadan and is often done as a community, with people gathering to break their fast together. Iftar is taken right after Maghrib time, which is around sunset.

#Japanese #Foodporn in #Singapore:
I am usually not keen on ramen as the soup tends to be too saltish or full of sodium or msg or the noodles are too soggy. But now I see why #Tonkotsu #Ramen Special won the top spot as the Critics' Choice in Timeout Singapore's Best Ramen Bowl - it was really really good! I finished the huge bowl of noodles, generous portion of delicious pork, giant sheet of seaweed and the lovely eggs. 
All Thanks to my #friend for sporting the as banner in the atrium of Parkway and insisted on eating at #Chef Keisuke Takeda's - Ramen Keisuke Tonkotsu King MATSURI. I loved it and wouldn't mind going back again.

From Wiki:  Tonkotsu (豚骨, "pork bone"; ) ramen usually has a cloudy white colored broth. It is similar to the Chinese baitang (白湯) and has a thick broth made from boiling pork bones, fat, and collagen over high heat for many hours, which suffuses the broth with a hearty pork flavor and a creamy consistency that rivals milk, melted butter or gravy (depending on the shop). It is a specialty of Kyushu, particularly Hakata-ku, Fukuoka (hence sometimes called "Hakata ramen"). #Ramen #Keisuke #Tonkotsu King #MATSURI

"Chamber of God" by Mujahidin Nurrahman @artstagesg D4

I stumbled across this beautiful and thought provoking piece by talented Bandung artist Mujahidin Nurrahman as I was leaving #ArtStageSg. I spent the most time checking out the gorgeous installation piece and was lucky to hear the story behind the inspiration for Chambers of God. The installation art piece was borne out of the Artist's desire to discuss the issue of war and conflict in the Middle East, how the world sees Islam and Muslims and includes a tie back to World War UK in the form of old photos and gas mask found in the flea markets of Paris. He painstakingly cut out the intricate Arabesque patterns on the screen and canvases. Go check it out if you're there. I thought it would be great for the Singapore Biennial actually.

21 - 24 Jan, 12:00 PM - 6:00 PM

post_caption:
Thaipusam in Singapore : "Dedicated to Lord Subramaniam, also known as Lord Murugan, the deity of youth, power and virtue, this festival is a time for repentance for devotees with celebrations carried out mainly at the temple. Devotees prepare themselves spiritually with extensive prayer and fasting before performing acts of penance or thanksgiving like carrying a kavadi from one temple to another. Often, sharp skewers are pierced through their tongues, cheeks and bodies as a practice of self-mortification."

Karipap Street - That’s what i call this place. Don’t be surprised if you see more than 5 shops selling Karipap or Indian Curry Puffs (the golden triangle crispy puffs) if you walked down Onan and Joo Chiat Road. The original and famous one is the Indian Muslim Bakery & Confectionery but in recent years, there is more options. Who is the best is a personal preference so try at least 3 of them to see which one is your favourite. Food is the one constant that unites Singaporeans so what better way to discover SG then to unearth the familiar taste that we grew up with.  #rediscoversg #sgigrediscovers #singaporerediscovers #sgfood

Jubilee Walk Tour Point 10: @acm_sg Asian Civilisation museum on the Singapore River. 
#AsianCivilisationsMuseum was originally a courthouse when it was built in 1867, but was subsequently used by the Colonial Secretariat and Legislative Council and known as the Government Offices. The adjacent square was named Empress Place in 1907 in honour of Britain's Queen Victoria, who also held the title Empress of India.
The building was converted into the Empress Place Museum in 1989 and became home to the Asian Civilisations Museum in 2003.

post_caption:
Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
龍南殿九皇大二帝爷千秋
九月初🗓🙏🙏🙏

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia.

Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. 

This year the festival has scaled down considerably due to the Covid pandemic. Devotees, however, are still welcome to pray to the dieties but have to observe the social distancing measures in the temples.

ALCHEMY | BY STARLIGHT ALCHEMY (SINGAPORE)

Date: 21 Aug & 22 Aug
Time: 8:00 PM, 9:30 PM, 11:00 PM
Venue: Singapore Art Museum, Front Lawn

Catch the exhilarating journey of reconciliation between Apollo from the world of Ethereal Light and Nuri from the world of Eternal Flame, told through three 25-minute segments during the night. Starlight Alchemy’s spectacular showcase of its multi-disciplinary flow arts combines a variety of aerial and large custom-made fire props, as well as LED technology performance props.

post_caption: 9-pound cannon, one of a pair originally used as decorations for the main gate of Fort Canning. The Sri Krishnan temple began as a shrine under a banyan tree in Waterloo Street in 1870. post_caption:
#Foodporn #Singapore #Food : "Ter Kar" or Braised Pig's Trotters. 
Decided to go down to a place I haven't been to in a while and eat something I haven't eaten in a while - at Han's Bak Kut Teh out at East Coast Lagoon Hawker Centre.  It's one of the best known but more for it's Ter Kar.  It used to be a favourite of mine and I'll make my way all the way down about once a month. It's sinfully rich and meaty , in this thick dark sweet sauce that the meat has been braised in half the night. I usually ask for the lean meat hence no skin.

It's almost as good as I remembered; used to be better with the mother when she was around cooking it. The meat would melt off the bone and so tender. The portion is huge, larger than my fist!

post_caption:
#Foodporn #Eating out in #Singapore especially at a #hawker center or #foodcourt means a staggering array and variety of local and regional and even international good. One can eat a different type for every meal for a month!

When you get a group of #Singaporeans together, they always overorder. 8 of us ordered nearly 15 dishes when we were at Lau Pa Sat or Telok Ayer Market, a historical and restored  colonial building turned food centre. The food ranged from good to not so good or weird tasting. Still a good place if you need to bring overseas visitors or it's late and you've got a large group in the vicinity.

We had : bak chor mee, Puerto Rican, char kuay teow, black carrot cake, white carrot cake, hokkien mee, mee goreng, satay, orh luk, bian mian and so much more....... #sgheritage  #igsingapore #food #foodlovers #shiok #streetfood

The wonderful thing about bringing friends visiting from overseas is you get to see your country through new eyes and a lot of time, go places you normally won't have gone....cos you know, you're not a tourist! I've got lots of friends visiting Singapore every month and also love playing local tourist - and have seen more of Singapore in the last 5 years than my entire life! It has been a grand adventure so far - and whoever says there is nothing to do in Singapore has not gotten their butt off to really explore the nooks, crannies and multi-cultural, multi-ethnic experiences and places available here. There's something on every day.

The 120-year-old Sri Senpaga Vinayagar Temple in Ceylon Road had its consecration ceremony recently - the Maha Kumbhabishegam, a highly auspicious ritual held every 12 years.

Highlights of the #NationalMuseumofSingapore : No ordinary table, this is THE original table where the British signed their surrender, and Singapore, over to the Japanese Army. ......................."The Singapore surrender  table (1940s) Teak ." On loan, courtesy of the Australian War Memorial" ..................."On 15  February  1942,  the  British  surrendered  unconditionally  to  the  Imperial  Japanese  Army.  The General  Officer  Commanding Malaya,  Lieutenant-General  Arthur  Percival,  signed the Instrument  of Surrender  document  on this  table  in the  boardroom of the Ford Factory  on  Bukit  Timah Road.  All British  and Allied  forces  were  ceded to Lieutenant-General  Tomoyuki  Yamashita of  the Imperial Japanese Army.  It  was donated by  Ford Malaysia to the Australian War Memorial in 1964. "
.......................................................................... Had a sneak peek at the National Museum of Singapore's new Permanent galleries. It's been Refreshed, Revamped and Revitalised to better showcase Singapore's history from 700 years ago till present day. It's certainly a fresh look with lots of modern technology incorporated to make the visit more interesting, interactive and immersive. Opens to the public on Sat, Sept 19 with free entry and loads of fun activities for all.

The  new permanent galleries are  the Singapore History  Gallery,  the  Life in Singapore: The Past 100 Years galleries and the Goh Seng Choo Gallery.

Rainbow over Jalan Bukit Merah in the morning. Welcoming sight in the morning, before the start of your day.

HDB Kim Tian 119:

Block 119B, 119C & 119D at Kim Tian Road are 30 storey HDB public housing flats in Bukit Merah, District 03, Singapore. It has a total of 200 units with 128 units of 4-room unit type and 72 units of 5-room unit type in every block. These flats were completed in 2001 and has a 80 years lease remaining.

HDB Membina 118:

Membina 118 have Block 118A, 118B, 118C & 118D at Jalan Membina are 30 storey HDB public housing flats in Bukit Merah, District 03, Singapore. It has a total of 172 units with 172 units of 4-room unit type in every block. These flats were completed in 2001 and has a 80 years lease remaining.

post_caption:
This cluster of HDB blocks at Balam Road were built between 1967 and 1973. A few years ago, they were given a new coat of paint and I love how they stand out with their red, yellow and blue façade, inspired by Dutch Modernist painter Piet Mondrain’s 1930 painting, “Composition with Red, Blue and Yellow” among the newer blocks in the same vicinity. Those trees in the midst also provide shade and bring some greenery to the surroundings.

I’m glad many of us in Singapore are fortunate to have a roof over our heads and stay safe especially during this COVID-19 pandemic.

post_caption:
We went on HydroDash, Singapore's first inflatable floating water park at Sentosa (Official) and it was a blast for all of us... though I think my kids were secretly laughing every time I fell into the sea. 😅
.
Floating in the sea just off Palawan Beach, HydroDash is an inflatable playground on water where kids and adults can climb, slide, leap and bounce to their hearts' content... if they can keep their balance! Because it sure cannot get more fun than balancing on floating platforms while clearing steep slopes and obstacles as one navigates the slippery obstacle course.
.

#Time stop a long time ago for this estate. Soon, it will begin life anew.
............................................................... Once 669 families lived in Blocks 74 to 80 at Commonwealth Drive. They were also known as Chap Lau Chu : 10-storey houses in Hokkien. The area is also known as Tanglin Halt, where some of the earliest HDB flats are to be found. The 7 blocks had been identified for redevelopment under Sers and residents moved out to new 40 story flats, nearby. Soon these flats from a bygone era will be demolished.

Today it held its farewell party "Goodbye 74 to 80 Commonwealth Drive" organised by My Queenstown.

Yeogi: a cosy and bright family styled restaurant that serves up affordable Korean fare, and almost all the dishes we tried are rave-worthy. Highlights are the crunchy seafood pancake ($15), garlic soy fried chicken ($18 for 10), and the addictive japchae which had strips of meat within ($15). The spam kimchi fried rice ($10) unfortunately was a tad too sour. No GST charged here, only service charge. Also complimentary hot/iced barley tea is served. Typical banchan is served (bean sprouts / kimchi / beancurd) too.  #sglgfood #yeogi

#Krishnattam #indianarts #kalaautsavam #esplanade

by Krishnattam Kalanilayam of Guruvayoor Devaswom
In association with Soorya (Singapore)
20 & 21 Nov 2015 : 7.30pm & 9pm
22 Nov 2015 : 7pm & 8.30pm
Outdoor Theatre

With roots dating back to 17th century northern Kerala, Krishnattam is an all-male temple dance drama that tells the story of Lord Krishna over a series of eight plays. Created by Manaveda, the Zamorin raja (king) of Calicut, in 1653, the play is performed today only at the temple dedicated to Lord Krishna in the town of Guruvayoor.

#ShareACokeSg while on my current obsession with the #ShareACoke #Sg50 #Singapore campaign. 
From the Coke Singapore website: 
The world-famous ‘Share a Coke’ campaign has arrived on The Little Red Dot and for the first time in Singapore, Coca-Cola cans and bottles will feature nicknames and phrases in place of the iconic Coca-Cola logo, to inspire people to share a Coke with those around them.

In celebration of Singapore’s 50th anniversary, from now until the end of August, Coke™, Coke zero™ and Coke light™ cans and bottles will feature commonly-used Singaporean terms such as “Auntie”, “Uncle”, “Ah Boy” and “Chiongster”; colloquial nicknames such as “BFF”, “Bestie”, “Babe” and “Bro”; classic expressions such as “I Love You” and “You’re the Best” , and favourite Singlish phrases such as “Gam Siah”, “Relak Lah” and “Chiong Ah”. #RediscoveringSingapore #ExploringSingapore #RediscoverSG #ExploreSG #InterestingSingapore #FunInSingapore

post_caption:
House of Tan Teng Niah -View 3
#sg_photocommunity #sgig #stb_sg #architecture #architecturephotography #architecture_hunter #colorful #vintage #singaporephotos #singapore #history #art #culture #traditionalart #rediscoversg #orientphotocontest2020 #orientfoto 

THIS VIVIDLY COLORFUL HOUSE WAS constructed in 1900 by a local businessman named Tan Teng Niah. At the time, the neighborhood was an industrial zone (Tan’s candy and rubber factories were located nearby) and many of Singapore’s ethnic-Chinese businessmen lived in similar villas.
Amid Singapore’s rapid economic growth and social change during the 20th century, the neighborhood evolved into what is now known as Little India. Most of the old merchant houses were razed to make way for modern commercial buildings and sleek skyscrapers. However, the Tan Teng Niah house survived, and during the 1980s, it underwent a full restoration to what people see today.

This is the national #monument, the Singapore 'Yu Huang Gong', Temple of The Heavenly Jade Emperor, located at 150 Telok Ayer Streer. Extensive restoration work was undertaken last few years to save the historic 170-year-old temple and has now been completed.

#Singapore #Parties: Had fun at the soft opening #party tonight at the latest #chichi place in town by the @indochine_group #Indochine Group - #ArnNan (which means Red Person) #Alfresco #Bar + #Bistro at @suntecsingapore  Destined to be THE latest in-place. 
The bar area is large, airy, and will be a great place to go with friends and hang out for a drink and bite. Pretty cool decor, lots of seating places, there will be a DJ console plus there was live music at tonight's party. This will be my go to place to bring friends who are in town.

Arn Nan by the IndoChine Group is sited at the new Suntec City Sky Gardens, 3 Temasek Boulevard #03-304/305.

Saying a prayer for peace, luck and wealth at the temple has been a culture and ritual for many a Chinese during the Chinese New Year.  The  Kwan Im Thong Hood Cho Temple in Waterloo St is one popular temple where thousands of devotees flock to to offer prayers at the stroke of midnight on the first day of CNY.  Many youths today have also practised these intangible heritage of religious culture passed down for generations.

ICYMI: All Singaporeans aged 18 and above will be receiving $100 worth of vouchers digitally accessible via Singpass to spend on staycations, local attractions and tours.⁠⠀
⁠⠀
The vouchers will be credited to you this December, perfect as a Christmas gift! It will be valid until June 2021 and can be used to offset ticket purchases and hotel stays so start planning your staycations now!⁠⠀
⁠⠀
The vouchers will also be distributed in denominations of $10 so it can be used in your preferred way, whether it’s spreading the $100 out across several visits or using it all up on a hotel stay.⁠⠀
⁠⠀
This is part of the $320 million SingapoRediscovers scheme announced last month, which is an effort by the government to promote local tourism amidst the pandemic as they are one of the most heavily affected sectors.⁠⠀
⁠⠀
🎡 What would you spend these vouchers on? Share with us in the comments below!⁠⠀
⁠⠀

Sri Senpaga Vinayagar Temple, situated on Ceylon Road, was established in the mid-19th century by the Ceylonese Tamils from Sri Lanka. Built on the architectural lines that was favoured in the ancient Chola kingdom of India, this temple is the second-oldest Hindu temple in Singapore. (Via Infopedia)

The 120-year-old Sri Senpaga Vinayagar Temple in Ceylon Road had its consecration ceremony recently - the Maha Kumbhabishegam, a highly auspicious ritual held every 12 years.
